{"q":"CMS481","stem":"Which of the following heart sounds are best heard with the bell of a stethoscope:<br>I. Opening snap<br>II. Systolic click<br>III. Third heart sound<br>IV. Mid diastolic murmur","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["I and IV","II and III only","III and IV","I, II and III only"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The bell of the stethoscope is designed to detect low-frequency (low-pitched) cardiac sounds.<br><br>The third heart sound (S3) is low-pitched, occurring in early diastole, and best heard with the bell.<br><br>Mid-diastolic murmurs, such as the rumble of mitral stenosis, are also low-frequency and optimally heard with the bell.<br><br>High-frequency sounds like opening snap and systolic click are better detected with the diaphragm.<br><br>Proper light placement of the bell preserves low-frequency sound transmission.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Opening snap is high-frequency, not heard with the bell.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Systolic click is high-frequency; only S3 is heard with the bell.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Includes systolic click, which is not detected with the bell.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS482","stem":"Consider the following statements for diagnosing ventricular aneurysm in a patient with recent myocardial infarction:<br>I. Paradoxical impulse on chest wall<br>II. Persistent ST elevation on ECG<br>III. Unusual bulge from cardiac silhouette on X-ray<br>IV. Presence of pulsus paradoxus<br>Which of the above are correct:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["I and II","I and IV","I, II and III","II, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Ventricular aneurysm usually develops after transmural myocardial infarction, most commonly involving the anterior wall.<br><br>Paradoxical bulging or impulse on the chest wall during systole is characteristic due to dyskinetic ventricular wall movement.<br><br>Persistent ST-segment elevation on ECG is a classical finding even weeks after MI.<br><br>Unusual bulge on chest X-ray may show localized enlargement of the cardiac silhouette corresponding to the aneurysm.<br><br>Pulsus paradoxus is not a feature of ventricular aneurysm; it is seen in conditions like cardiac tamponade.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Correctly includes I and II but misses the X-ray finding (III).<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect because pulsus paradoxus (IV) is not related to ventricular aneurysm.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect because paradoxical impulse (I) is essential, and pulsus paradoxus (IV) is irrelevant.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS483","stem":"Which one of the following statements is correct for subcutaneous nodules in Rheumatic fever:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["They are present over flexor aspect of forearm","They are painful tender nodules","The usual size of these nodules is 3-5 cm","They typically appear more than 3 weeks after onset of other clinical manifestations"],"subject":"Medicine, Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Subcutaneous nodules in Rheumatic fever are firm, non-tender, mobile nodules over extensor surfaces such as elbows, knees, and occiput.<br><br>They usually appear later in the disease course, often more than 3 weeks after initial manifestations like fever, arthritis, and carditis.<br><br>The size of these nodules is typically small, 0.5-2 cm, not 3-5 cm.<br><br>Presence of nodules is a minor criterion in the revised Jones criteria but is highly specific for severe disease.<br><br>They are usually painless and transient, disappearing within a few weeks.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; nodules appear on extensor, not flexor, surfaces.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; nodules are non-tender.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; nodules are smaller than 3 cm typically.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS484","stem":"Which one of the following is correct with regard to Carey Coombs murmur:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Soft systolic murmur due to mitral regurgitation","Mid-systolic murmur due to mitral valvulitis","Harsh early diastolic murmur due to aortic regurgitation","Blowing late systolic murmur due to aortic stenosis"],"subject":"Medicine, Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Carey Coombs murmur is a soft, mid-diastolic murmur heard at the apex in patients with acute rheumatic fever. (Note: The provided option B says \"Mid-systolic\", which contradicts the standard \"mid-diastolic\" description given in the solution text and medical literature, but it is marked as the correct answer in the source).<br><br>It is caused by mitral valvulitis leading to increased flow across the mitral valve without significant structural damage.<br><br>The murmur is short, low-pitched, and rumbling, and disappears as the inflammation resolves.<br><br>Unlike mitral stenosis, there is no opening snap in Carey Coombs murmur.<br><br>It is an important auscultatory sign of active carditis in rheumatic fever.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; mitral regurgitation produces a holosystolic murmur, not Carey Coombs murmur.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; early diastolic murmur is characteristic of aortic regurgitation, unrelated to Carey Coombs murmur.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; aortic stenosis produces a systolic ejection murmur, not mid-diastolic.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS485","stem":"Which of the following statements is correct regarding Opening Snap (OS) in a patient of mitral stenosis:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["OS is heard with the help of stethoscope","Intensity of OS becomes louder when valve is calcified","OS moves closer to the second sound (S2) as the stenosis becomes more severe","OS is best heard at the second left intercostal space"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Opening Snap (OS) is an early diastolic sound caused by the sudden opening of a stenotic mitral valve.<br><br>The interval between S2 and OS decreases as mitral stenosis becomes more severe due to higher left atrial pressure.<br><br>OS is high-pitched and best heard with the diaphragm at the apex in the left lateral decubitus position.<br><br>The intensity of OS may decrease with valve calcification, as a stiff valve does not snap as distinctly.<br><br>OS is a key auscultatory feature distinguishing rheumatic mitral stenosis from other diastolic murmurs.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> True in general, but too nonspecific, does not indicate the unique clinical significance.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; calcified valves often produce a duller or absent OS.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; OS is best heard at the apex, not the second left intercostal space.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS486","stem":"Which one of the following responses to intravenous adenosine is correctly matched:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Atrial fibrillation - Termination","Atrio-ventricular nodal reentrant tachycardia - Termination","Ventricular tachycardia - Termination and complete recovery","Atrial flutter - Termination and complete recovery"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Adenosine transiently blocks AV nodal conduction, making it highly effective in terminating AV nodal reentrant tachycardia (AVNRT).<br><br>It does not terminate atrial fibrillation or atrial flutter but may briefly slow ventricular response, helping diagnosis.<br><br>Adenosine is ineffective in ventricular tachycardia and should be used cautiously; termination is rare.<br><br>The drug is short-acting, with rapid onset and recovery, making it safe for acute termination of AVNRT.<br><br>Adenosine may produce transient flushing, chest discomfort, or brief asystole, but these resolve quickly.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; atrial fibrillation is not terminated by adenosine.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; ventricular tachycardia is usually unresponsive to adenosine.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; atrial flutter is not terminated by adenosine; it may transiently slow AV conduction.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS487","stem":"Consider the following steps for using a metered dose inhaler (MDI):<br>I. Incline the head backward to minimize oropharyngeal deposition<br>II. Remove the cap and shake the inhaler<br>III. Breathe out gently and place the mouthpiece in the mouth<br>IV. Hold the breath for 10 seconds<br>V. Start inhaling slowly and on deep inspiration, depress the canister to release a dose<br>Which one of the following is the correct sequence of using MDI:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["II, I, III, V, IV","II, III, II, V","II, III, V, IV","II, III, V, I, IV"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Remove cap and shake inhaler (II) ensures proper mixing of medication.<br><br>Head tilt backward (I) helps in better airway alignment and reduces oropharyngeal deposition.<br><br>Exhale gently and position mouthpiece (III) prepares lungs for optimal drug intake.<br><br>Slow inhalation with simultaneous actuation (V) is critical for effective lung deposition.<br><br>Breath holding (IV) allows maximum drug settling in lower airways.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Repeats shaking step, making sequence incorrect. Missing breath-holding, which is essential.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Head tilt step is omitted. Though partially correct, it is incomplete.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Head tilt done after inhalation, which is incorrect timing. Must be done before inhalation for proper airway alignment.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS488","stem":"Under the Stepwise Approach to the management of Bronchial Asthma, which one of the following is the correct initial treatment at Step 1 for a patient diagnosed with Asthma:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Low dose inhaled corticosteroid","Low dose inhaled corticosteroid plus oral corticosteroid","Low dose inhaled corticosteroid plus long acting anti-muscarinic agents","Low dose inhaled corticosteroid plus leukotriene antagonist"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Step 1 management of asthma involves mild, intermittent symptoms, and the initial therapy is usually a low-dose inhaled corticosteroid (ICS) for anti-inflammatory control.<br><br>Low-dose ICS reduces airway inflammation and prevents progression without systemic side effects.<br><br>Oral corticosteroids are reserved for exacerbations or severe asthma, not initial therapy.<br><br>Long-acting anti-muscarinic agents or leukotriene antagonists are add-on therapies in higher steps if control is not achieved.<br><br>Stepwise therapy emphasizes starting with the minimum effective therapy and escalating based on symptom control.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; oral corticosteroids are not used in initial Step 1 therapy due to systemic side effects.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; long-acting anti-muscarinic agents are used as add-on therapy in more severe or uncontrolled asthma.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; leukotriene antagonists are optional add-ons, not first-line for Step 1.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS489","stem":"A 62-year-old male chronic smoker has been diagnosed with Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD). On Pulmonary function testing, the ratio of Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 second (FEV1) to Forced Vital Capacity (FVC) was 0.6 and his FEV1 was 70% of predicted. What is the correct stage of severity as per GOLD criteria:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Stage I - Mild","Stage II - Moderate","Stage III - Severe","Stage IV - Very severe"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>GOLD criteria define COPD severity based on post-bronchodilator FEV1 % predicted in patients with FEV1/FVC < 0.7.<br><br>Stage I (Mild): FEV1 >= 80% predicted<br><br>Stage II (Moderate): FEV1 50-79% predicted<br><br>Stage III (Severe): FEV1 30-49% predicted<br><br>Stage IV (Very Severe): FEV1 < 30% predicted or FEV1 < 50% with chronic respiratory failure<br><br>In this patient, FEV1 = 70% predicted, so he falls into Stage II - Moderate COPD. FEV1/FVC ratio of 0.6 confirms obstructive defect.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Stage I requires FEV1 >= 80%.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Stage III requires FEV1 30-49%.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Stage IV requires FEV1 < 30% or presence of chronic respiratory failure.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS490","stem":"Which one of the following correctly denotes the inheritance pattern of cystic fibrosis:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Autosomal Dominant","Autosomal Recessive","X-linked Dominant","X-linked Recessive"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Cystic fibrosis follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern.<br><br>Cystic fibrosis is caused by mutations in the CFTR gene.<br><br>The CFTR gene is located on chromosome 7.<br><br>Since chromosome 7 is an autosome, the disease is not X-linked.<br><br>Affected individuals usually inherit two defective alleles, one from each carrier parent.<br><br>Carrier parents are usually clinically asymptomatic.<br><br>Therefore, the inheritance pattern of cystic fibrosis is autosomal recessive.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Autosomal dominant disorders usually manifest when only one mutant allele is present. They often show vertical transmission across generations. Cystic fibrosis requires mutations in both copies of the CFTR gene. Hence, this option is incorrect.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> X-linked dominant disorders are caused by mutations on the X chromosome. Cystic fibrosis is caused by mutation on chromosome 7, not the X chromosome. Therefore, this option is incorrect.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> X-linked recessive disorders mainly affect males and are transmitted through carrier females. Cystic fibrosis is not located on the X chromosome. It affects males and females equally. Hence, this option is incorrect.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS491","stem":"Which one of the following terms denotes the extensive sclerosis of the skin of the chest wall and set of ribs that resembles what is seen as a rare manifestation of systemic sclerosis:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Filial Chest","Hidebound Chest","Barrel Chest","Pigeon Chest"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Hidebound chest refers to the extensive sclerosis of the skin and underlying tissues of the chest wall seen in systemic sclerosis (scleroderma).<br><br>The skin becomes tight, rigid, and adherent to underlying structures, limiting chest wall expansion.<br><br>This results in a characteristic restriction of respiratory movements and a firm, immobile chest wall.<br><br>It is a rare but classic manifestation of systemic sclerosis, usually associated with advanced disease.<br><br>Other chest deformities such as barrel chest or pigeon chest are related to pulmonary disease or skeletal anomalies, not skin sclerosis.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; \"Filial chest\" is not a recognized term in this context.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; barrel chest is seen in COPD/emphysema, not systemic sclerosis.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; pigeon chest (pectus carinatum) is a congenital skeletal deformity, unrelated to skin sclerosis.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS492","stem":"Consider the following pleural fluid findings: pH - 7.6, Pleural fluid protein - 6.5 g/dL, Serum total protein - 6.5 g/dL, Pleural fluid LDH - 100 U/L, Serum LDH - 300 U/L. What is the likely diagnosis:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Pancreatitis","Myxoedema","Sarcoidosis","Rheumatoid arthritis"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Myxoedema (severe hypothyroidism) is associated with exudative or borderline pleural effusions that are usually high in protein but low in LDH, giving a protein-rich but low enzyme content effusion.<br><br>Pleural fluid/serum protein ratio in this case = 6.5/6.5 = 1.0, which is very high, suggesting protein-rich effusion typical of myxoedema.<br><br>pH is usually slightly alkaline (~7.6) in hypothyroid effusions.<br><br>Other causes like pancreatitis, rheumatoid arthritis, and sarcoidosis typically show lower protein ratios, inflammatory changes, or higher LDH levels.<br><br>The effusion is usually bilateral, serous, and responds to thyroid hormone replacement.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; pancreatitis usually produces exudative effusion with elevated amylase.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; sarcoidosis effusions are lymphocytic, exudative, not as protein-rich.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; rheumatoid arthritis causes exudative effusions with low glucose and high LDH.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS493","stem":"'Masson Bodies' formed due to proliferation of immature collagen are a characteristic histological finding seen in which one of the following conditions:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Lymphocytic Interstitial Pneumonia","Cryptogenic Organizing Pneumonia","Desquamative Interstitial Pneumonitis","Respiratory Bronchiolitis"],"subject":"Medicine, Pathology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Cryptogenic Organizing Pneumonia (COP) is characterized histologically by Masson bodies, which are plugs of granulation tissue (fibroblasts and immature collagen) within alveolar ducts, alveoli, and bronchioles.<br><br>The surrounding lung architecture is preserved, unlike in fibrotic interstitial pneumonias.<br><br>Masson bodies represent the organization phase of pneumonia, where fibroblastic tissue fills alveolar spaces.<br><br>Clinically, COP presents with subacute respiratory symptoms, patchy infiltrates on imaging, and good response to corticosteroids.<br><br>Recognizing Masson bodies helps differentiate COP from other interstitial lung diseases.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Lymphocytic interstitial pneumonia shows diffuse lymphocytic infiltration, not Masson bodies.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Desquamative interstitial pneumonitis shows alveoli filled with macrophages, not collagen plugs.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Respiratory bronchiolitis is characterized by pigmented macrophages in bronchioles, not Masson bodies.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS494","stem":"Consider the following statements regarding respiratory function in old age:<br>I. There is increasing ventilation-perfusion mismatch<br>II. There is a decreased ventilatory response to hypoxia and hypercarbia<br>III. There is a linear reduction in oxygenating capacity reflected by decreased FEV1/FVC<br>IV. There is decline in Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 second (FEV1) of about 22% per year after the forties.<br>Which of the statements given above are correct:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I, II and III","II, III and IV","II and III","I, II and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Physiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Aging is associated with increasing ventilation-perfusion (V/Q) mismatch, contributing to mild hypoxemia.<br><br>Ventilatory response to hypoxia and hypercarbia decreases with age, reducing compensatory mechanisms during respiratory stress.<br><br>FEV1 declines with age, but FEV1/FVC ratio is usually preserved until late, so linear reduction in FEV1/FVC is incorrect.<br><br>FEV1 declines by about 20-30 mL per year after the fourth decade, which is reflected in statement IV.<br><br>Overall, age-related changes result in reduced lung elasticity, increased residual volume, and decreased vital capacity.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; FEV1/FVC does not decline linearly with age.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; FEV1/FVC is preserved; IV is correct but III is incorrect.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; III is incorrect as FEV1/FVC does not decline linearly with age.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS495","stem":"Which one of the following statements is correct in respect of pulmonary involvement in rheumatoid disease:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Rheumatoid pulmonary nodules are usually asymptomatic and detected incidentally on imaging","Rheumatoid pulmonary nodules are often solitary and located near hilum","Pleural effusion in these patients is transudative and usually bilateral","Combination of pleural effusion and pneumoconiosis in these patients is known as Caplan syndrome"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Rheumatoid pulmonary nodules are typically multiple, asymptomatic, and discovered incidentally on chest imaging.<br><br>These nodules are usually subpleural, more commonly in the upper lobes, and can vary in size.<br><br>Pleural effusions in rheumatoid disease are exudative, often unilateral, and may show low glucose and low pH.<br><br>Caplan syndrome refers to rheumatoid nodules in patients with pneumoconiosis, not pleural effusions.<br><br>Pulmonary involvement can include interstitial lung disease, pleural disease, and airway disease, with nodules being a common incidental finding.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; nodules are typically multiple and peripheral, not solitary near the hilum.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; pleural effusions are exudative, not transudative, and often unilateral.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Caplan syndrome is pneumoconiosis plus nodules, not effusions.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS496","stem":"Which one of the following conditions is a complication of bacterial pharyngitis involving infection of the internal jugular vein leading to thrombosis and metastatic dispersal to the lungs:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Cystic Fibrosis","Chronic Pulmonary Aspergillosis","Lemierre syndrome","Wegener's granulomatosis"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Lemierre syndrome is a rare but severe complication of bacterial pharyngitis, usually caused by Fusobacterium necrophorum.<br><br>Infection spreads from the oropharynx to the internal jugular vein, causing septic thrombophlebitis.<br><br>Metastatic septic emboli frequently involve the lungs, causing pulmonary infiltrates, abscesses, and empyema.<br><br>Clinical features include fever, sore throat, neck pain/swelling, and respiratory symptoms from embolic spread.<br><br>Early recognition and intravenous antibiotics are crucial to prevent morbidity and mortality.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; cystic fibrosis is a genetic disorder causing chronic lung infections, not post-pharyngitis thrombosis.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; chronic pulmonary aspergillosis is fungal and not related to internal jugular vein thrombosis.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Wegener's granulomatosis (GPA) is an autoimmune vasculitis, not a post-infectious syndrome.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS497","stem":"A 42-year-old man with a history of alcohol dependency presents with progressive abdominal distension over 4 months. Clinical examination reveals a shifting dullness. Which one of the following drugs is used to relieve this abdominal distension:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Octreotide","Propranolol","Lactulose","Spironolactone"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The patient has ascites, likely secondary to alcoholic cirrhosis, as suggested by progressive abdominal distension and shifting dullness.<br><br>Spironolactone, a potassium-sparing diuretic, is the first-line drug for mobilizing ascitic fluid by antagonizing aldosterone and promoting sodium excretion.<br><br>It reduces fluid retention gradually and is often combined with loop diuretics for more effective diuresis.<br><br>Octreotide is used in variceal bleeding, not for ascites.<br><br>Propranolol is used to prevent variceal hemorrhage by reducing portal pressure, not to relieve fluid accumulation.<br><br>Lactulose is used to treat hepatic encephalopathy by reducing ammonia levels, not ascites.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; octreotide is for variceal bleeding, not ascites.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; propranolol reduces portal hypertension but does not relieve ascitic fluid.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; lactulose is for hepatic encephalopathy, not fluid accumulation.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS498","stem":"Which one of the following is the investigation of choice for diagnosing the presence of stones in the gall-bladder:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Transabdominal ultrasound","Erect X-ray of abdomen","Capsule endoscopy","Computed Tomography"],"subject":"Surgery, Radiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Transabdominal ultrasound is the investigation of choice for detecting gallstones due to its high sensitivity and specificity, non-invasiveness, and cost-effectiveness.<br><br>It can detect stones as small as 2-3 mm, and can also assess gallbladder wall thickness and biliary ductal dilatation.<br><br>Ultrasound does not expose the patient to radiation, making it safe and repeatable.<br><br>CT is less sensitive for cholesterol stones, which are often radiolucent.<br><br>Erect X-ray can detect only radiopaque stones, which are a minority.<br><br>Capsule endoscopy is primarily for small intestine evaluation, not gallbladder stones.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; X-ray detects only radiopaque stones, missing most gallstones.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; capsule endoscopy is not used for gallbladder evaluation.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; CT can detect stones but is less sensitive than ultrasound for gallbladder stones.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS499","stem":"Which one of the following biologic agents used in the treatment of inflammatory bowel disease acts by inhibiting the enzyme 'Janus Kinase':","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Infliximab","Adalimumab","Vedolizumab","Tofacitinib"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Tofacitinib is an oral Janus kinase (JAK) inhibitor that blocks intracellular signaling of multiple pro-inflammatory cytokines involved in ulcerative colitis.<br><br>It is indicated for moderate-to-severe ulcerative colitis in patients who have failed conventional therapy or biologics.<br><br>Infliximab and Adalimumab are anti-TNF-alpha monoclonal antibodies, not JAK inhibitors.<br><br>Vedolizumab is an anti-integrin monoclonal antibody that selectively blocks gut lymphocyte trafficking.<br><br>JAK inhibition reduces cytokine-mediated inflammation without targeting TNF-alpha or integrins directly.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Infliximab is an anti-TNF agent, not a JAK inhibitor.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; Adalimumab is also an anti-TNF agent.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Vedolizumab blocks a4b7 integrin, not JAK.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS500","stem":"Melanosis coli, which occurs due to long-term consumption of stimulant laxatives, is a brown-black pigmentation of colonic mucosa due to accumulation of which one of the following pigments?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Melanin","Haemosiderin","Lipofuscin","Haemoglobin"],"subject":"Medicine, Pathology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Lipofuscin pigment accumulates in macrophages of the colonic mucosa due to apoptosis of epithelial cells induced by chronic stimulant laxative use (e.g., senna, cascara).<br><br>The pigment gives a characteristic brown-black discoloration, known as melanosis coli, despite not being melanin.<br><br>The condition is benign and reversible upon stopping laxatives.<br><br>Lipofuscin is a wear-and-tear pigment derived from oxidized lipids and proteins.<br><br>The appearance may look alarming but has no malignant potential.<br><br>Other pigments such as melanin or haemosiderin are not involved in this condition.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; melanin is not deposited in melanosis coli.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; haemosiderin deposition occurs in iron overload, not laxative-induced pigmentation.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; haemoglobin pigments are not associated with melanosis coli.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS501","stem":"Consider the following with regard to Gilbert Syndrome:<br>I. Autosomal recessive trait of a mutation in gene for UDP-glucuronyl transferase enzyme<br>II. Elevation of unconjugated bilirubin<br>III. No stigma of chronic liver dysfunction other than jaundice<br>IV. Early liver biopsy recommended in patients with possible Gilbert Syndrome<br>Which of the above are correct?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I and II only","II and III only","I, II and III","II, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Genetics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Gilbert syndrome is a benign hereditary condition characterized by isolated unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia (mild elevation).<br><br>It is classically autosomal dominant, not autosomal recessive; hence Statement I is incorrect.<br><br>Patients have no signs of chronic liver disease, and liver enzymes remain normal; Statement III is correct.<br><br>Liver biopsy is not required in typical cases; diagnosis is clinical and based on labs; Statement IV is incorrect.<br><br>Symptoms may be triggered by fasting, illness, stress, leading to mild jaundice.<br><br>The condition is harmless and requires no treatment.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Statement I is wrong regarding inheritance.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; includes the incorrect Statement I.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Statement IV is not true-biopsy is not recommended.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS502","stem":"The single most important treatment and prognostic factor in alcohol-related liver disease is:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Abstinence","Cessation of alcohol consumption","Liver transplantation","High dose vitamin E"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Abstinence from alcohol is the most effective treatment and the strongest prognostic factor in alcohol-related liver disease.<br><br>Continued alcohol use accelerates progression to cirrhosis, portal hypertension, and hepatic decompensation.<br><br>Sustained abstinence can lead to partial or complete reversal of fatty liver and stabilization of alcoholic hepatitis/cirrhosis.<br><br>No medical therapy (e.g., antioxidants, steroids) confers benefits comparable to complete alcohol cessation.<br><br>Liver transplantation improves survival only in end-stage cases, but abstinence remains essential even post-transplant.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; wording is similar, but \"abstinence\" (complete, sustained cessation) is the precise and accepted term.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; reserved for end-stage liver disease and not the primary or most important treatment.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; vitamin E has no proven benefit in alcoholic liver disease.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS503","stem":"A 40-year-old man with chronic pancreatitis presents with new skin nodules over the abdomen that are erythematous/violaceous/skin-colored and tender. Biopsy confirms the diagnosis. Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnosis?","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Pancreatic panniculitis","Anti-gliadin antibody disease","Vitamin D (25-OH) D level","Vitamin B12 levels"],"subject":"Medicine, Dermatology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Pancreatic panniculitis is a rare manifestation of chronic pancreatitis caused by circulating pancreatic enzymes (especially lipase) leading to fat necrosis in subcutaneous tissue.<br><br>Characteristic lesions include painful, erythematous or violaceous nodules, most commonly on the lower limbs and abdomen.<br><br>Biopsy typically shows lobular panniculitis with \"ghost cells\" (necrotic adipocytes lacking nuclei).<br><br>Strongly associated with pancreatic inflammation, pancreatic carcinoma, or pancreatic pseudocyst.<br><br>Cutaneous lesions may precede or coincide with worsening pancreatic disease.<br><br>Lab findings often show elevated lipase and amylase levels.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; anti-gliadin antibodies relate to celiac disease, not tender panniculitic nodules.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; vitamin D levels have no relation to panniculitis.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; vitamin B12 levels do not explain this clinical picture.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS504","stem":"Which one of the following is correct regarding angiotensin vasopressin antagonist Tolvaptan:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["It is useful in hypovolemic hyponatremia","It antagonises the V2 receptor","It should be used for at least 1 year","It is oral drug"],"subject":"Pharmacology, Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Tolvaptan is a selective V2 receptor antagonist, blocking vasopressin-mediated water reabsorption in the renal collecting ducts.<br><br>It is primarily used in euvolemic and hypervolemic hyponatremia, such as in syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH) or heart failure.<br><br>The drug promotes free water excretion (aquaresis) without significant loss of electrolytes.<br><br>Treatment duration is generally short-term, titrated to achieve gradual correction of serum sodium; long-term use is not standard.<br><br>Tolvaptan is administered orally, but the defining characteristic is its V2 receptor antagonism, not just the route of administration.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Tolvaptan is not used in hypovolemic hyponatremia, as fluid replacement is the treatment.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; therapy is short-term and not recommended for routine 1-year use.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; although oral, this is not the key pharmacologic property.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS505","stem":"Which one of the following conditions is caused by mutations in the gene that encodes the sodium-potassium-2-chloride cotransporter (NKCC2), leading to polyuria, sodium wasting, hypokalemia, hypermagnesaemia and hypercalciuria:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Alport syndrome","Bartter syndrome","Fanconi syndrome","Gitelman syndrome"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Bartter syndrome is caused by mutations in the NKCC2 transporter in the thick ascending limb of Henle's loop, resulting in defective sodium, potassium, and chloride reabsorption.<br><br>Clinically, it presents with polyuria, polydipsia, hypokalemia, metabolic alkalosis, and hypercalciuria.<br><br>Hypermagnesemia may also be observed due to altered tubular handling of magnesium.<br><br>The condition is autosomal recessive and often presents in childhood, sometimes as antenatal Bartter syndrome with polyhydramnios.<br><br>Treatment involves potassium supplementation, NSAIDs, and supportive care to reduce renal salt wasting.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Alport syndrome is a genetic glomerular disease causing hematuria and progressive renal failure.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Fanconi syndrome involves generalized proximal tubular dysfunction with glycosuria, phosphaturia, and aminoaciduria.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Gitelman syndrome involves distal convoluted tubule defects, hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia, and hypocalciuria, not hypercalciuria.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS506","stem":"A 52-year-old male has uncontrolled diabetes. Which one of the following tests will help in early detection of nephropathy:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Blood urea level","Serum creatinine level","Ultrasonography","Urine albumin"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Urine albumin measurement, specifically microalbuminuria (30-300 mg/day), is the earliest marker of diabetic nephropathy.<br><br>Microalbuminuria precedes decline in glomerular filtration rate and rise in serum creatinine.<br><br>Early detection allows timely intervention with glycemic control, blood pressure management, and ACE inhibitors or ARBs to slow disease progression.<br><br>Blood urea and serum creatinine levels rise only after significant nephron loss, making them late markers.<br><br>Ultrasonography detects structural changes but is not sensitive for early nephropathy.<br><br>Regular screening for microalbuminuria is recommended annually in all patients with diabetes.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; blood urea rises late and is influenced by diet and hydration.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; serum creatinine rises after substantial renal damage.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; ultrasonography cannot detect early functional changes.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS507","stem":"Autosomal dominant mutations in which one of the following genes may cause focal segmental glomerulosclerosis associated with abnormal genitalia, Wilms' tumour, and mental retardation:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["WT1","INF2","LMX1B","APOL1"],"subject":"Medicine, Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>WT1 gene mutations cause Denys-Drash syndrome, characterized by focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS), abnormal genitalia, Wilms' tumor, and sometimes mental retardation.<br><br>WT1 is a transcription factor essential for kidney and gonadal development.<br><br>FSGS develops early in life and can progress to end-stage renal disease.<br><br>Wilms' tumor risk is significantly elevated in patients with WT1 mutations, hence surveillance is crucial.<br><br>INF2 mutations primarily cause FSGS without genital anomalies or Wilms' tumor.<br><br>LMX1B mutations cause nail-patella syndrome, with proteinuria and nephropathy but distinct skeletal anomalies.<br><br>APOL1 variants increase risk of FSGS in individuals of African ancestry, but are not associated with Wilms' tumor or genital abnormalities.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; INF2 mutations cause hereditary FSGS without Wilms' tumor or genital defects.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; LMX1B mutations cause nail-patella syndrome, not Wilms' tumor.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; APOL1 variants predispose to FSGS in certain populations, not syndromic features.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS508","stem":"Kidney damage and Glomerular Filtration Rate (GFR) value between 15-29 mL/min/1.73 m&#178; are found in which stage of Chronic Kidney Disease:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Stage 2 (mild)","Stage 3A (mild to moderate)","Stage 4 (severe)","Stage 5 (kidney failure)"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Stage 4 CKD is defined by severe reduction in GFR (15-29 mL/min/1.73 m&#178;) with evidence of kidney damage.<br><br>Patients may experience symptoms of uremia, including fatigue, fluid retention, hypertension, and electrolyte disturbances.<br><br>This stage requires preparation for renal replacement therapy (dialysis or transplantation).<br><br>Stage 2 CKD: GFR 60-89 mL/min/1.73 m&#178;, mild decrease.<br><br>Stage 3A: GFR 45-59 mL/min/1.73 m&#178;, mild to moderate decrease.<br><br>Stage 5 CKD: GFR <15 mL/min/1.73 m&#178;, representing end-stage renal disease (kidney failure).<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Stage 2 is mild with GFR 60-89.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; Stage 3A has GFR 45-59.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Stage 5 is GFR <15, not 15-29.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS509","stem":"Which one of the following hereditary tubulo-interstitial kidney diseases has an autosomal recessive mode of inheritance:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Medullary cystic kidney disease type 1","Medullary cystic kidney disease type 2","Nephronophthisis","Juvenile hyperuremic nephropathy"],"subject":"Medicine, Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Nephronophthisis is an autosomal recessive hereditary tubulo-interstitial kidney disease.<br><br>It is characterized by chronic tubulointerstitial nephritis, corticomedullary cysts, and progressive renal failure, often in childhood or adolescence.<br><br>Presents with polyuria, polydipsia, and anemia before kidney function declines.<br><br>Medullary cystic kidney disease types 1 and 2 are autosomal dominant disorders, typically presenting in adulthood.<br><br>Juvenile hyperuricemic nephropathy (familial) can also be autosomal dominant and presents with gout and renal failure.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; type 1 is autosomal dominant.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; type 2 is autosomal dominant.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; usually autosomal dominant inheritance.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS510","stem":"Which of the following findings in a patient are suggestive of acute nephritis:<br>I. Hematuria<br>II. Oliguria<br>III. Reduced size of both kidneys<br>IV. Edema","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and III","II and IV","I, II and III only","I and IV"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Hematuria is a hallmark feature of acute nephritis due to glomerular inflammation.<br><br>Patients often present with cola-colored urine, indicating RBC leakage through damaged glomeruli.<br><br>Edema occurs due to salt and water retention and reduced renal function.<br><br>Periorbital edema is especially characteristic in acute glomerulonephritis.<br><br>These features together strongly suggest acute nephritic syndrome.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Hematuria is correct, but reduced kidney size suggests chronic kidney disease, not acute nephritis. In acute nephritis, kidneys are usually normal or enlarged due to inflammation.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Oliguria is a feature of acute nephritis, but not always present. Edema is correct, but missing hematuria, which is a key feature.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Hematuria and oliguria can occur in acute nephritis. However, reduced kidney size indicates chronicity, not acute disease.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS511","stem":"A 35-year-old male presents with increased urine output (~4 L/day), urinary osmolality 200 mOsmol/L, and normal serum sodium. What are the various differential diagnoses:<br>I. Psychogenic polydipsia<br>II. Solute diuresis<br>III. Central diabetes insipidus<br>IV. Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and II only","I and III only","II and IV","I and IV only"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Polyuria with dilute urine (low osmolality) and normal serum sodium suggests water diuresis rather than solute diuresis.<br><br>Psychogenic polydipsia leads to excessive water intake, resulting in low urine osmolality.<br><br>Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus causes inability of kidneys to respond to vasopressin, producing large volumes of dilute urine.<br><br>Central diabetes insipidus can present similarly, but often leads to mild hypernatremia if water intake is insufficient.<br><br>Solute diuresis (e.g., hyperglycemia) is usually associated with high urine osmolality and electrolyte abnormalities, not seen here.<br><br>Evaluation often includes water deprivation test and desmopressin response to differentiate central vs nephrogenic causes.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; solute diuresis is not consistent with low urine osmolality and normal serum sodium.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; central DI usually alters serum sodium if water intake is inadequate.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; solute diuresis excluded as above.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS512","stem":"Contralateral homonymous upper quadrantanopsia is the type of visual loss seen when the lesion is located at which one of the following anatomical locations?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Frontal lobe","Temporal lobe","Parietal lobe","Occipital lobe"],"subject":"Medicine, Ophthalmology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Lesions of the temporal lobe involving Meyer's loop cause contralateral homonymous upper quadrantanopsia (also known as \"pie in the sky\" defect).<br><br>Meyer's loop carries the inferior optic radiation fibers, which correspond to the superior visual field.<br><br>Temporal lobe lesions may occur due to tumors, trauma, stroke, or infections affecting this pathway.<br><br>Parietal lobe lesions instead produce lower quadrantanopsia (\"pie on the floor\").<br><br>Occipital lobe lesions may cause homonymous hemianopia with or without macular sparing.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; frontal lobe lesions do not typically cause specific quadrantanopsias.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; parietal lobe lesions produce contralateral lower quadrantanopsia.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; occipital lobe lesions usually cause homonymous hemianopia.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS513","stem":"Which of the following are clinical features of migraine?<br>I. It is associated with dilatation of extracranial vessels<br>II. Common migraine is seen without Aura<br>III. Aura is most often visual","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["I, II and III","I and III only","II and III only","I and II only"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Migraine involves dilatation of extracranial vessels, contributing to the throbbing, pulsatile nature of the headache.<br><br>The most common type of migraine is migraine without aura (formerly called \"common migraine\").<br><br>When present, aura is most often visual, such as scintillating scotomas or flashing lights.<br><br>Migraine aura may also include sensory, speech, or motor disturbances, but visual symptoms predominate.<br><br>These features align with the typical presentation of migraine as described in clinical neurology.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; statement II is also correct.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; statement I is also correct.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; statement III is also correct.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS514","stem":"A 50-year-old man presents with brief episodes of lancinating unilateral facial pain involving the maxillary division. Pain is triggered by washing his face with cold water. What is the most likely diagnosis?","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Migraine","Medication overuse headache","Chronic paroxysmal hemicrania","Trigeminal neuralgia"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Trigeminal neuralgia presents with sudden, severe, electric shock-like or lancinating pain in the distribution of one or more branches of the trigeminal nerve.<br><br>The maxillary division (V2) is a commonly affected branch.<br><br>Pain is typically triggered by light stimuli such as washing the face, cold wind, chewing, or talking.<br><br>Attacks are brief, lasting seconds, but can recur in clusters.<br><br>It most commonly affects adults over 50 years of age.<br><br>Migraine and chronic paroxysmal hemicrania do not present with such brief, trigger-induced shock-like pains.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; migraine presents with prolonged pulsatile headache, not brief shock-like facial pain.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; medication-overuse headache is chronic, dull, and diffuse.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; chronic paroxysmal hemicrania causes orbital/temporal pain and responds to indomethacin.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS515","stem":"Which of the following are trigger factors for seizures?<br>I. Sleep deprivation<br>II. Missed doses of antiepileptic drugs<br>III. Recreational drug misuse<br>IV. Physical exhaustion","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and III only","I and IV only","I, II and III only","I, II, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Sleep deprivation lowers seizure threshold and is a well-known precipitant.<br><br>Missed doses of antiepileptic drugs can trigger breakthrough seizures in patients with epilepsy.<br><br>Recreational drug misuse (e.g., cocaine, amphetamines, alcohol withdrawal) can precipitate seizures.<br><br>Physical exhaustion and stress may also act as seizure triggers by affecting metabolic and neuronal stability.<br><br>Seizure triggers vary among individuals, but these four factors are commonly recognized and should be addressed in seizure management.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; excludes II and IV, which are also triggers.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; excludes II and III, which are important triggers.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; excludes IV, which can precipitate seizures.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS516","stem":"Which one of the following childhood epileptic disorders often needs long-term treatment with antiepileptic drugs:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Benign neonatal seizures","Febrile seizures","Benign rolandic epilepsy","Juvenile myoclonic epilepsy"],"subject":"Pediatrics ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Juvenile myoclonic epilepsy (JME) is a generalized epilepsy syndrome that typically begins in adolescence and is characterized by myoclonic jerks, generalized tonic-clonic seizures, and sometimes absence seizures.<br><br>JME usually requires long-term or lifelong antiepileptic therapy, often with valproate or other broad-spectrum AEDs, to prevent seizure recurrence.<br><br>Benign rolandic epilepsy often remits spontaneously in adolescence and may not require prolonged treatment.<br><br>Benign neonatal seizures are usually self-limited and often do not need long-term therapy.<br><br>Febrile seizures are typically short-lived, triggered by fever, and generally do not require chronic AED treatment.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; benign neonatal seizures are usually transient.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; febrile seizures rarely require long-term treatment.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; benign rolandic epilepsy often remits and may not need prolonged therapy.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS517","stem":"Which of the following are clinical features of Parkinson's disease?<br>I. Reduced eye blinking<br>II. Drooling of saliva<br>III. Soft voice<br>IV. Macrographia","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["I, II and III","I, III and IV","II, III and IV","I, II, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Reduced eye blinking is a feature of hypomimia, reflecting decreased facial expressiveness.<br><br>Drooling of saliva (sialorrhea) occurs due to impaired swallowing and reduced spontaneous swallowing frequency.<br><br>Soft voice (hypophonia) is common due to reduced motor control of speech muscles.<br><br>Macrographia (abnormally large handwriting) is not a typical feature of Parkinson's disease; instead, micrographia (small, cramped handwriting) is characteristic.<br><br>These motor and non-motor features reflect dopaminergic neuron loss in the substantia nigra.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; macrographia is wrong; Parkinson's causes micrographia.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; reduced eye blinking (I) is missing.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; includes macrographia, which is not a Parkinson's feature.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS518","stem":"A 35-year-old female presents with easy fatigability. Investigations show hemoglobin 7 g/dL; red cell morphology is normocytic normochromic, and her iron studies and red cell indices are normal. Which one of the following conditions favors the diagnosis:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Iron deficiency anemia","Sideroblastic anemia","Folate deficiency anemia","Intravascular hemolysis"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Intravascular hemolysis can present with normocytic, normochromic anemia because red cells are destroyed after normal maturation.<br><br>Hemoglobin is reduced, but iron studies are normal, as iron is recycled from destroyed red cells.<br><br>Other lab features may include elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), indirect hyperbilirubinemia, and hemoglobinuria or hemosiderinuria.<br><br>Folate or vitamin B12 deficiencies typically cause macrocytosis, not normocytic anemia.<br><br>Iron deficiency anemia is usually microcytic, hypochromic with low ferritin.<br><br>Sideroblastic anemia is often microcytic or dimorphic with characteristic ring sideroblasts on bone marrow.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; iron deficiency anemia shows microcytosis and low ferritin.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; sideroblastic anemia shows ring sideroblasts and microcytosis, not normocytic.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; folate deficiency produces macrocytic anemia, not normocytic.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS519","stem":"A 46-year-old man on a vegan diet for a decade presents with numbness and weakness in lower limbs, macrocytosis, and a history of surviving on whole grains through narrow intestines. Which one of the following investigations is advisable for diagnosis in this case:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Serum protein electrophoresis","Anti-gliadin antibodies","Vitamin D (25OH) D level","Vitamin B12 levels"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Vitamin B12 deficiency is common in long-term vegans due to absence of animal-derived foods.<br><br>Neurological symptoms such as paresthesia, numbness, and weakness, especially in lower limbs, indicate subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord.<br><br>Macrocytosis on peripheral smear supports megaloblastic anemia secondary to B12 deficiency.<br><br>History of limited intestinal absorption (e.g., short gut, resections) further predisposes to B12 deficiency.<br><br>Measurement of serum vitamin B12 levels is the first-line investigation for diagnosis.<br><br>Early diagnosis allows treatment with parenteral or high-dose oral vitamin B12 to prevent permanent neurological damage.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; serum protein electrophoresis is used for multiple myeloma, not B12 deficiency.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; anti-gliadin antibodies are for celiac disease, not vitamin B12 deficiency.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; vitamin D deficiency does not cause macrocytosis or neurological symptoms described.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS520","stem":"A 65-year-old male with type 2 diabetes presents with progressive burning and tingling sensation in both feet, especially at night. Examination reveals decreased vibration sense and absent ankle reflexes. Which one of the following medications is recommended as first-line therapy for his symptoms?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Ibuprofen","Pregabalin","Amitriptyline","Acetaminophen"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The patient presents with classic symptoms of diabetic peripheral neuropathy (DPN), characterized by distal symmetric polyneuropathy with burning, tingling, and loss of vibration sense and ankle reflexes.<br><br>First-line pharmacological treatments for painful DPN include pregabalin, gabapentin, duloxetine, and tricyclic antidepressants (TCAs) like amitriptyline. (Note: While amitriptyline is also a first-line option, pregabalin is explicitly FDA-approved and widely considered a top-tier first-line agent with a favorable side effect profile compared to TCAs in the elderly).<br><br>These agents modulate pain pathways in the central nervous system.<br><br>Simple analgesics like ibuprofen and acetaminophen are generally ineffective for neuropathic pain.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Ibuprofen (NSAID) is not effective for neuropathic pain.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Amitriptyline is also a first-line agent, but pregabalin is often preferred due to fewer anticholinergic side effects in the elderly.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Acetaminophen is ineffective for neuropathic pain.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS521","stem":"Which one of the following causes low-volume erythrocytosis:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Polycythemia Rubra Vera","Exogenous testosterone therapy","Gaisbock's syndrome","High altitude"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Gaisböck's syndrome is a form of relative erythrocytosis, where hemoglobin and hematocrit are elevated due to reduced plasma volume, not an actual increase in red cell mass.<br><br>It is commonly seen in hypertensive, middle-aged men with stress or obesity.<br><br>Polycythemia vera and exogenous testosterone therapy cause absolute erythrocytosis, with actual increase in red cell mass.<br><br>High-altitude adaptation leads to absolute erythrocytosis due to chronic hypoxia stimulating erythropoietin production.<br><br>Clinical distinction is important for management; Gaisböck's syndrome may normalize with volume expansion and lifestyle modification.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; polycythemia vera is absolute erythrocytosis with increased red cell mass.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; testosterone therapy stimulates erythropoiesis, causing absolute erythrocytosis.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; high altitude increases red cell mass (absolute erythrocytosis), not low-volume.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS522","stem":"First-line therapy in chronic phase of chronic myeloid leukemia is:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Rituximab","Thalidomide","Imatinib","Chlorambucil"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Imatinib is a tyrosine kinase inhibitor (TKI) that specifically targets the BCR-ABL fusion protein, the pathogenic driver in chronic myeloid leukemia (CML).<br><br>It is considered first-line therapy for newly diagnosed patients in the chronic phase, leading to high rates of complete cytogenetic and molecular responses.<br><br>Therapy is usually oral, daily, and long-term, with regular monitoring of BCR-ABL transcript levels.<br><br>Rituximab is an anti-CD20 monoclonal antibody used in B-cell malignancies, not CML.<br><br>Thalidomide is used in multiple myeloma and some myelodysplastic syndromes, not CML.<br><br>Chlorambucil is an alkylating agent used in chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL) and other lymphoid malignancies, not first-line in CML.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Rituximab is not used in CML.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; Thalidomide is not effective for CML.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Chlorambucil is not first-line therapy for CML.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS523","stem":"With regard to management of idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP), consider the following statements:<br>I. All patients with ITP with platelet count less than 10,000 should be treated with glucocorticoid therapy<br>II. For patients with spontaneous bleeding, 40 mg of dexamethasone should be administered for 4 days<br>III. Intravenous immunoglobulin can be used as rescue treatment<br>IV. Life-saving bleeding should be treated with platelet transfusion","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I, II and III","II, III and IV","II and III only","I, II and IV"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>IVIG (intravenous immunoglobulin) is used as a rescue therapy in ITP for patients with severe thrombocytopenia or active bleeding.<br><br>Life-threatening bleeding requires immediate platelet transfusion even though platelets may be rapidly destroyed.<br><br>Dexamethasone 40 mg/day for 4 days is a recognized regimen for acute management of ITP with bleeding.<br><br>Not all patients with platelet count <10,000 require glucocorticoids immediately if asymptomatic; observation may be sufficient in some cases. The management strategy depends on bleeding risk, platelet count, and clinical presentation, rather than platelet count alone.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; glucocorticoids are not mandatory for all patients <10,000 if asymptomatic.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; excludes life-saving platelet transfusion.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; excludes IVIG, which is standard rescue therapy.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS524","stem":"Which of the following drugs can cause secondary weight gain?<br>I. Insulin<br>II. Propranolol<br>III. Orlistat<br>IV. Thyroxine","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I, II and IV","I and III","II, III and IV","I and II only"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Insulin therapy can lead to weight gain due to enhanced glucose uptake and anabolic effects.<br><br>Propranolol, a non-selective beta-blocker, may cause mild weight gain by reducing metabolic rate and masking hypoglycemia.<br><br>Orlistat is a lipase inhibitor and causes weight loss, not gain.<br><br>Thyroxine replacement typically reduces weight in hypothyroid patients, not increases it.<br><br>Secondary weight gain due to drugs is often dose-dependent and reversible after discontinuation.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; thyroxine does not cause weight gain.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; orlistat causes weight loss, not gain.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; includes orlistat and thyroxine incorrectly.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS525","stem":"Under which one of the following conditions is HPA axis suppression likely to result in a crisis due to adrenal insufficiency following withdrawal of glucocorticoids?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["If glucocorticoids have been given by intravenous route for five days","If glucocorticoids have been administered orally for one week","If glucocorticoids have been administered repeatedly within the previous year","If the dose is less than equivalent of 5 mg prednisolone per day"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Repeated or prolonged glucocorticoid therapy over months can suppress the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, leading to adrenal insufficiency on withdrawal.<br><br>Short-term glucocorticoid use (less than 1-2 weeks) rarely causes HPA suppression.<br><br>Very low doses (<5 mg prednisolone/day) are unlikely to suppress the HPA axis.<br><br>Withdrawal after repeated courses within a year increases the risk of adrenal crisis if abrupt.<br><br>Patients at risk may require gradual tapering of steroids and monitoring for adrenal insufficiency symptoms.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; 5-day IV therapy usually does not cause HPA suppression.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; 1-week oral therapy rarely suppresses adrenal function.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; doses <5 mg prednisolone/day are generally safe for the HPA axis.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS526","stem":"Wilson's disease has which of the following inheritance:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["X-linked recessive","Autosomal dominant","Autosomal recessive","It is an acquired disease"],"subject":"Medicine, Pediatrics, Genetics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Wilson's disease is caused by mutations in the ATP7B gene, leading to impaired copper transport and accumulation.<br><br>It follows an autosomal recessive inheritance, requiring biallelic mutations for disease manifestation.<br><br>Both parents of an affected individual are typically carriers without clinical symptoms.<br><br>Clinical features include hepatic dysfunction, neurological symptoms, psychiatric manifestations, and Kayser-Fleischer rings in the cornea.<br><br>Early diagnosis and chelating therapy (e.g., penicillamine, trientine) or zinc therapy can prevent progression.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Wilson's disease is not X-linked.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; it is not autosomal dominant.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; it is a genetic disorder, not acquired.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS527","stem":"Which of the following can be used for the management of severe hyperkalemia?<br>I. Intravenous calcitonin<br>II. Intravenous sodium bicarbonate<br>III. Oral sodium polystyrene sulphate<br>IV. Intravenous calcium gluconate","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I, II and IV","I and III only","II, III and IV","II and IV only"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Intravenous calcium gluconate stabilizes the cardiac membrane, preventing life-threatening arrhythmias in severe hyperkalemia.<br><br>Intravenous sodium bicarbonate helps shift potassium into cells, particularly when metabolic acidosis is present.<br><br>Oral sodium polystyrene sulphate works slowly and is not suitable for acute severe hyperkalemia; it is used for chronic or mild cases.<br><br>Calcitonin is not effective for hyperkalemia and is used for hypercalcemia instead.<br><br>Acute management focuses on cardioprotection, intracellular potassium shift, and eventual potassium removal if needed.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; calcitonin is not used for hyperkalemia.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; calcitonin and oral resin are inappropriate for acute severe cases.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; oral polystyrene is too slow for acute management.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS528","stem":"Which one of the following conditions can cause euvolemic hyponatremia:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Adrenocortical failure","Hypothyroidism","Nephrotic syndrome","Burns"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Hypothyroidism can cause euvolemic hyponatremia due to reduced free water clearance and impaired renal water excretion.<br><br>Adrenocortical failure (Addison's disease) usually causes hypovolemic hyponatremia due to aldosterone deficiency.<br><br>Nephrotic syndrome leads to edematous states, causing hypervolemic hyponatremia.<br><br>Burns result in hypovolemic hyponatremia because of fluid losses.<br><br>Euvolemic hyponatremia is most commonly seen in SIADH, hypothyroidism, and glucocorticoid deficiency without salt loss.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; typically hypovolemic hyponatremia.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; typically hypervolemic hyponatremia.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; typically hypovolemic hyponatremia.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS529","stem":"Which one among the following vectors transmits the filaria Loa loa","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Simulium","Chrysops","Culex","Culicoides"],"subject":"Medicine, PSM","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Chrysops (deer fly) is the vector of Loa loa, responsible for transmitting microfilariae to humans through its bite.<br><br>Loa loa infection causes loiasis, characterized by Calabar swellings and migration of adult worms across the conjunctiva.<br><br>Simulium transmits Onchocerca volvulus, causing onchocerciasis (river blindness).<br><br>Culex transmits Wuchereria bancrofti (lymphatic filariasis) and various arboviruses.<br><br>Culicoides (biting midges) transmit Bluetongue virus and other animal pathogens, not Loa loa.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Simulium transmits Onchocerca volvulus.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Culex transmits Wuchereria bancrofti, not Loa loa.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Culicoides does not transmit human filaria.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS530","stem":"Which of the following is the most favourable prognostic parameter in Bell's palsy:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Incomplete paralysis in the first week","Mild CSF lymphocytosis","Denervation in EMG after 10 days","Pain behind the ear"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Incomplete paralysis in the first week indicates that some nerve fibers are still functioning, which is associated with rapid and complete recovery.<br><br>Mild CSF lymphocytosis is a nonspecific finding and does not predict prognosis in Bell's palsy.<br><br>Denervation in EMG after 10 days indicates severe nerve involvement and is associated with slower recovery.<br><br>Pain behind the ear is a common early symptom but does not correlate with prognosis.<br><br>Early partial motor function is the strongest predictor of good functional recovery.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; CSF changes are not prognostic.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; EMG denervation suggests severe involvement and poorer prognosis.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; pain is a symptom, not a prognostic factor.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS531","stem":"Which one of the following groups of drugs is ineffective against gram positive bacteria:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Monobactams","Glycopeptides","Fluoroquinolones","First generation cephalosporins"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology, Microbiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Monobactams (e.g., Aztreonam) have a narrow spectrum limited to aerobic gram-negative rods such as Pseudomonas, E. coli, and Klebsiella.<br><br>They are inactive against gram-positive bacteria and anaerobes, making them ineffective for infections caused by these organisms.<br><br>Glycopeptides (e.g., Vancomycin) are highly active against gram-positive bacteria, including MRSA.<br><br>Fluoroquinolones have broad-spectrum activity, covering many gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria.<br><br>First-generation cephalosporins are effective against most gram-positive cocci, including Staphylococcus aureus and Streptococcus species.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; glycopeptides are effective against gram-positive bacteria.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; fluoroquinolones have activity against many gram-positive bacteria.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; first-generation cephalosporins are active against gram-positive cocci.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS532","stem":"Which one of the following statements is correct regarding leprosy:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Type 1 Leprosy Reaction is also called erythema nodosum leprosum","Type 2 Leprosy Reaction is an immune complex mediated syndrome called arthus phenomenon","'Lion face' appearance is seen in tuberculoid leprosy","Nose is the last site of involvement in lepromatous leprosy"],"subject":"Medicine, Dermatology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Type 2 Leprosy Reaction (Erythema Nodosum Leprosum, ENL) is an immune complex-mediated hypersensitivity reaction (Arthus phenomenon) seen in lepromatous leprosy.<br><br>Type 1 Leprosy Reaction is a cell-mediated delayed-type hypersensitivity reaction, usually seen in borderline leprosy, and is not ENL.<br><br>'Lion face' (facial infiltration, thickening of skin) is a feature of lepromatous leprosy, not tuberculoid leprosy.<br><br>In lepromatous leprosy, the nose is commonly affected early, not the last site.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Type 1 reaction is a delayed-type hypersensitivity reaction, not ENL.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; 'Lion face' is characteristic of lepromatous leprosy.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; nasal involvement occurs early in lepromatous leprosy.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS533","stem":"A 56 year old gardener presents with an ulcerative nodule with purulent discharge in his right hand. When he had a prick with a thorn, at the same site around a month back. Which one of the following infections is most likely:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Chromoblastomycosis","Mycetoma","Phaeohyphomycosis","Sporotrichosis"],"subject":"Medicine, Dermatology, Microbiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Sporotrichosis is a subcutaneous fungal infection caused by Sporothrix schenckii, typically occurring after traumatic inoculation (e.g., thorn prick) in gardeners or farmers.<br><br>It presents as ulcerative nodules or nodular lymphangitis along the lymphatic channels, often with purulent discharge.<br><br>Chromoblastomycosis is a chronic fungal infection with verrucous lesions, usually slow-growing and rarely ulcerative.<br><br>Mycetoma presents as swelling with sinus tracts and grains, often over the foot, and is chronic.<br><br>Phaeohyphomycosis causes pigmented nodules or cysts, often in immunocompromised patients, and is less associated with traumatic inoculation.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; chromoblastomycosis is usually verrucous, not ulcerative post-trauma.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; mycetoma has characteristic grains in sinus tracts and is usually chronic.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; phaeohyphomycosis is less common, typically immunocompromised, and lacks lymphatic spread.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS534","stem":"A 36 year old man presents with decreased appetite, mouth soreness, diarrhoea and irritability. On examination a pigmented scaly rash around the neck is found. Which one of the following items in his diet has a bearing on his disease:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Rice","Wheat","Corn","Fish"],"subject":"Medicine, PSM, Dermatology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The patient presents with pellagra, characterized by the 3 Ds: dermatitis, diarrhea, and dementia (irritability).<br><br>Pellagra is caused by niacin (vitamin B3) deficiency or tryptophan deficiency.<br><br>Corn (maize) is deficient in niacin and tryptophan, and if consumed as a staple without proper processing (nixtamalization), it can lead to pellagra.<br><br>Rice and wheat are less likely to cause niacin deficiency because they contain more available tryptophan and niacin.<br><br>Fish is a good source of niacin and does not contribute to pellagra.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; rice is not a cause of pellagra.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; wheat is not typically associated with niacin deficiency.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; fish provides niacin and is protective.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS535","stem":"Acrodermatitis enteropathica is an autosomal recessive metabolic disorder which affects the absorption of which one of the following micronutrients?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Iodine","Zinc","Iron","Selenium"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Dermatology, Genetics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Acrodermatitis enteropathica is caused by mutations in the SLC39A4 gene, which impairs intestinal absorption of zinc.<br><br>The condition typically presents in infants after weaning, with dermatitis, alopecia, and diarrhea&#8212;the classic triad.<br><br>Zinc is essential for numerous enzymes and immune function; deficiency leads to characteristic periorificial and acral dermatitis.<br><br>Early diagnosis and lifelong zinc supplementation lead to complete recovery.<br><br>Iron, iodine, and selenium deficiencies do not produce this classical presentation.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; iodine deficiency causes hypothyroidism and goiter.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; iron deficiency leads to anemia, not acral dermatitis.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; selenium deficiency does not produce this clinical picture.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS536","stem":"Consider the following statements with regard to the treatment of vitamin A deficiency:<br>I. Repeated high doses of retinol can cause liver damage and teratogenicity<br>II. Acute overdose of vitamin A may lead to increased intracranial pressure<br>III. Regular vitamin A supplementation is recommended for pregnant women even in countries where vitamin A deficiency is not endemic<br>IV. Excessive intake of carotene may cause harmless orange pigmentation of the skin.<br>Which of the statements given above are correct?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I, II and III","I, II and IV","I, III and IV","II, III and IV"],"subject":"PSM, Medicine, Obstetrics and Gynaecology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Repeated high doses of retinol (preformed vitamin A) can cause hepatic toxicity and are teratogenic, especially risky in pregnancy.<br><br>Acute hypervitaminosis A presents with increased intracranial pressure, headache, nausea, and papilledema.<br><br>Routine vitamin A supplementation is not recommended in pregnancy in non-endemic areas because of risk of teratogenicity, making statement III false.<br><br>Excessive beta-carotene intake can cause carotenemia, a harmless orange pigmentation of skin, especially over palms and soles.<br><br>Therefore, I, II, and IV are correct.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; statement III is false.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; statement II is true but omitted.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; statement I is true and should be included.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS537","stem":"The Koebner phenomenon is seen in which one of the following conditions:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Psoriasis","Acne Vulgaris","Behcet's disease","Leprosy"],"subject":"Medicine, Dermatology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The Koebner phenomenon refers to the appearance of new lesions at sites of trauma in patients with certain skin diseases.<br><br>It is classically seen in psoriasis, where scratches, cuts, or other minor trauma can precipitate psoriatic plaques.<br><br>It can also be observed in lichen planus and vitiligo, but is most characteristic of psoriasis.<br><br>Acne vulgaris, Behcet's disease, and leprosy do not typically show Koebner phenomenon.<br><br>Recognizing this phenomenon is important in clinical dermatology to prevent worsening of lesions due to trauma.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; acne lesions are related to follicular occlusion, not trauma-induced.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Behcet's disease involves mucocutaneous lesions but not via Koebner phenomenon.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; leprosy lesions are not induced by trauma.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS538","stem":"Consider the following regarding the human hair growth cycle:<br>I. Anagen is a phase of active hair growth.<br>II. Telogen is a transitional phase.<br>III. Catagen is a resting phase.<br>Which of the statements given above is/are correct?","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["I only","III only","I and II only","I, II and III"],"subject":"Medicine, Dermatology, Physiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Statement I is correct because Anagen represents the active growth phase of the hair follicle, during which the cells of the hair root divide rapidly and produce the hair shaft.<br><br>The duration of the anagen phase typically spans 2 to 7 years, and it determines the ultimate maximum length of an individual's hair.<br><br>Statement II is incorrect because Telogen is actually the resting phase, not the transitional phase; during this period, the hair follicle remains completely inactive for about 3 months before the hair is shed.<br><br>Statement III is incorrect because Catagen is the short transitional phase (lasting roughly 2 to 3 weeks) that signals the end of active growth, where the hair follicle shrinks and detaches from the dermal papilla.<br><br>Misplacement of definitions in Statements II and III is a classic trap, as the true chronological order of the cycle moves from active growth (Anagen) to regression (Catagen) and finally to rest (Telogen).<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Catagen is mischaracterized as the resting phase in Statement III, whereas its true physiological role is to act as a highly controlled, regressive involution phase.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Telogen is misdefined as a transitional phase in Statement II, failing to recognize that it represents a prolonged static period where the mature \"club hair\" is held in place.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> A complete jumbling of the definitions for the second and third statements invalidates this \"all of the above\" selection.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS539","stem":"Consider the following statements regarding oculocutaneous albinism:<br>I. The disease results from genetic abnormalities leading to destruction of melanocytes.<br>II. Type I albinism is due to a defect in the tyrosinase gene.<br>III. Patients may present with poor vision, nystagmus and alternating strabismus.<br>IV. Patients are at an increased risk of sunburn or developing skin cancer.<br>Which of the statements given above are correct?","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I, II and III","I, II and IV","I, III and IV","II, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Dermatology, Genetics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Oculocutaneous albinism (OCA) is caused by genetic defects in melanin synthesis, not destruction of melanocytes, so statement I is incorrect.<br><br>Type I OCA is due to a mutation in the tyrosinase gene, leading to defective melanin production.<br><br>Patients present with ocular manifestations: poor vision, nystagmus, and strabismus.<br><br>Lack of melanin increases susceptibility to sunburn and skin cancers.<br><br>Understanding the distinction between melanocyte destruction and enzyme defects is crucial for diagnosis.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; statement I is false.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; statement I is false.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; statement I is false and statement II is missing.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS540","stem":"A 42 year old man presented with recurrent oral ulcers since one year, episodes of redness of eye and genital ulcers. Which one of the following tests is of diagnostic value?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Mantoux test","Drug-sensitivity test","Pathergy test","Patch test"],"subject":"Medicine, Dermatology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Pathergy test is used in the diagnosis of Behçet's disease, where minor trauma (like a needle prick) leads to a papule or pustule at the site after 24-48 hours.<br><br>Recurrent oral and genital ulcers with ocular involvement are characteristic of Behçet's disease.<br><br>Mantoux test is used for tuberculosis; not diagnostic for Behçet's.<br><br>Drug-sensitivity tests are relevant for allergic reactions or drug eruptions.<br><br>Patch test is used for allergic contact dermatitis, not systemic autoimmune disorders.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Mantoux is for TB diagnosis, not Behçet's disease.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; drug-sensitivity testing is unrelated.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; patch test is for contact allergy only.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS541","stem":"Which of the following joints are commonly affected in osteoarthritis:<br>I. First metatarsophalangeal joint<br>II. Proximal interphalangeal joint<br>III. Ankle joint<br>IV. 5th and 6th cervical vertebrae joint.<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["I and II only","III and IV only","I, II and IV only","I, II, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Surgery","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Osteoarthritis (OA) commonly affects weight-bearing and frequently used joints, especially distal joints of the hand and lower limbs.<br><br>First metatarsophalangeal joint (big toe) is frequently involved, leading to hallux rigidus.<br><br>Proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joints are commonly affected in OA, presenting as Bouchard's nodes.<br><br>The cervical spine, particularly C5-C6, can develop osteoarthritic changes with facet joint involvement.<br><br>Ankle joint is rarely affected in primary OA; involvement usually follows trauma or secondary OA.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; omits cervical spine involvement.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; ankle is rarely affected in primary OA, and cervical involvement alone is insufficient.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; includes ankle joint, which is not commonly affected in primary OA.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS542","stem":"Which of the following are causes of reversible dementia:<br>I. Hypothyroidism.<br>II. Vitamin B12 deficiency.<br>III. Dementia with Lewy body.<br>IV. Thiamine deficiency.<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I, II and III","II and III only","II, III and IV","I, II and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Psychiatry ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Hypothyroidism can cause cognitive impairment and memory deficits that are reversible with thyroid hormone replacement.<br><br>Vitamin B12 deficiency leads to neurological and cognitive dysfunction, which may improve with supplementation if detected early.<br><br>Thiamine deficiency (as in Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome) can cause reversible cognitive deficits with prompt thiamine administration.<br><br>Dementia with Lewy body is a neurodegenerative condition and is not reversible; treatment is only symptomatic.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; includes dementia with Lewy body, which is irreversible.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; omits hypothyroidism and thiamine deficiency.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; includes Lewy body dementia, which is irreversible.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS543","stem":"Which of the following are clinical features of Fronto-Temporal Dementia:<br>I. Personality change<br>II. Language disturbance<br>III. Memory may be preserved in early stages<br>IV. Anti-cholinesterases are the drug of choice for treatment.<br>Select the correct answer:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I, II and IV","I, II and III","I, III and IV","II, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Psychiatry ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Personality change is a hallmark feature of fronto-temporal dementia (FTD), often presenting as disinhibition or apathy.<br><br>Language disturbance such as progressive non-fluent aphasia or semantic deficits is commonly seen.<br><br>Memory may be preserved in early stages, distinguishing FTD from Alzheimer's disease.<br><br>Anti-cholinesterases are not the drug of choice; they have limited benefit in FTD and may worsen behavioral symptoms.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; anti-cholinesterases (IV) are not recommended.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; anti-cholinesterases (IV) are not recommended, and memory may be preserved (III) is correct.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; memory is often preserved (III), and anti-cholinesterases (IV) are not useful.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS544","stem":"Which one of the following is the myelinating cell of the Central Nervous System?","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Astrocyte","Microglia","Schwann cell","Oligodendrocyte"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Oligodendrocytes are responsible for forming myelin sheaths around CNS axons, enabling rapid saltatory conduction.<br><br>Astrocytes provide structural and metabolic support to neurons but do not myelinate axons.<br><br>Microglia are the resident immune cells of the CNS, involved in phagocytosis and inflammation.<br><br>Schwann cells myelinate peripheral nervous system (PNS) axons, not CNS axons.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; astrocytes support neurons but do not myelinate.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; microglia are immune cells, not myelinating cells.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Schwann cells myelinate PNS, not CNS axons.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS545","stem":"Which one of the following is the correct description of Mee's lines, seen in chronic arsenic poisoning?","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Transverse white lines on nails of fingers and toes","Transverse red lines on the skin of palms and soles","Parallel transverse lines on the skin of fingers and toes","Transverse red lines on the nails of fingers and toes"],"subject":"Medicine, Toxicology, Dermatology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Mee's lines are transverse white lines on the nails (also called leukonychia striata) that move distally as the nail grows.<br><br>They are a classic sign of chronic arsenic poisoning, but can also be seen in other systemic insults like acute poisoning, chemotherapy, or severe illness.<br><br>The lines are due to disrupted nail matrix formation during periods of systemic toxicity.<br><br>Transverse red lines or skin lesions are not characteristic of Mee's lines.<br><br>These lines are not painful and serve as a diagnostic clue in relevant exposure history.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; red lines on palms and soles are not Mee's lines.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Mee's lines are on nails, not skin.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; the lines are white, not red, on nails.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS546","stem":"Fomepizole is an antidote used to treat poisoning from which of the following substances:<br>I. Methanol<br>II. Digoxin<br>III. Cocaine<br>IV. Ethylene glycol.<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I and II","I and III","I and IV","II and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology, Toxicology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Fomepizole is a competitive inhibitor of alcohol dehydrogenase, preventing the metabolism of toxic alcohols into their harmful metabolites.<br><br>It is used in methanol poisoning, preventing formation of formic acid which causes metabolic acidosis and visual disturbances.<br><br>It is also used in ethylene glycol poisoning, preventing formation of glycolic and oxalic acids which can cause renal failure.<br><br>Digoxin toxicity is treated with digoxin-specific antibody fragments, not fomepizole.<br><br>Cocaine poisoning is managed with supportive care, benzodiazepines, and in severe cases, vasodilators or antiarrhythmics; fomepizole has no role.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; digoxin is not treated with fomepizole.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> This option code in source matches \"I and III\" but the correct answer is \"I and IV\" which aligns with Option C in the source image logic. (Wait, let me double check the source... Ah, Option 3 is \"I and IV\" and is marked as Correct Answer: 3). Therefore, Option C represents the correct code combination.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; digoxin is not treated with fomepizole.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS547","stem":"The 4AT Test is a screening tool for detection of delirium. Which of the following parameters are included in the 4AT tool:<br>I. Alertness<br>II. Apnoea<br>III. Abbreviated Mental Test (AMT4)<br>IV. Attention.<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["I, II and III","I, II and IV","I, III and IV","II, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Psychiatry","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The 4AT tool is a rapid clinical test for delirium and cognitive impairment.<br><br>It includes assessment of Alertness, Abbreviated Mental Test (AMT4), and Attention.<br><br>Acute change or fluctuating course is also considered as part of the overall assessment.<br><br>Apnoea is not included in the 4AT screening tool.<br><br>The 4AT can be performed quickly at the bedside without special training.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Apnoea is not part of the 4AT.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; Apnoea is not included.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Apnoea is not included.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS548","stem":"Which of the following combinations of lab test results is indicative of heavy alcohol consumption, with more than 60% sensitivity and specificity?","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Gamma glutamyl transferase (GGT) > 35 U/L and alkaline phosphatase > 45 U/L","Carbohydrate-deficient transferrin (CDT) > 20 U/L and serum uric acid > 7 mg/dL","High normal MCV > 91 fL and CDT > 20 U/L","GGT > 35 U/L and CDT > 20 U/L"],"subject":"Medicine, Pathology, Psychiatry","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>GGT and CDT combination is a highly sensitive and specific marker for chronic heavy alcohol use.<br><br>GGT reflects hepatocellular enzyme induction due to alcohol consumption.<br><br>Carbohydrate-deficient transferrin (CDT) increases with sustained alcohol intake and is a specific biomarker for heavy drinking.<br><br>The combination improves diagnostic accuracy compared to either marker alone.<br><br>High MCV or elevated serum uric acid alone are less specific and can be influenced by other conditions.<br><br>This combination is useful in screening, monitoring abstinence, and detecting relapse.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; alkaline phosphatase is nonspecific and does not improve sensitivity for alcohol use.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; serum uric acid is not a reliable marker of alcohol consumption.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; high MCV is nonspecific and alone does not confirm heavy drinking.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS549","stem":"What is the antidote for belladonna poisoning?","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Physostigmine","Amitriptyline","Fluoxetine","Flumazenil"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology, Toxicology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Physostigmine is a reversible cholinesterase inhibitor that increases acetylcholine levels at synapses, counteracting anticholinergic toxicity seen in belladonna poisoning.<br><br>Belladonna contains atropine and other tropane alkaloids, which cause anticholinergic effects such as dry mouth, mydriasis, tachycardia, urinary retention, and delirium.<br><br>Supportive care may include activated charcoal if ingestion is recent and symptomatic management of hyperthermia, agitation, or seizures.<br><br>Amitriptyline is a tricyclic antidepressant and does not reverse anticholinergic toxicity.<br><br>Fluoxetine is an SSRI and has no role in poisoning.<br><br>Flumazenil (written as Fluanzolil in source, likely typo) is an antidote for benzodiazepines, not belladonna.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; amitriptyline is not an antidote and may worsen anticholinergic toxicity.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; fluoxetine has no antidotal effect.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; not used in belladonna poisoning.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS550","stem":"Which one of the following prevents gastrointestinal absorption of thallium:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Prussian blue","Penicillamine","Potassium permanganate","Atropine"],"subject":"Medicine, Toxicology, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Prussian blue acts by binding thallium in the gastrointestinal tract, forming an insoluble complex that is excreted in feces, thus reducing systemic absorption.<br><br>It is the treatment of choice for thallium poisoning.<br><br>Penicillamine is a chelating agent used in heavy metal poisoning such as copper, not thallium.<br><br>Potassium permanganate is used for topical disinfection and certain ingestions but does not prevent thallium absorption.<br><br>Atropine is an anticholinergic agent and has no role in thallium poisoning.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; penicillamine does not prevent thallium absorption.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; potassium permanganate is not used for thallium.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; atropine is unrelated to thallium poisoning.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS551","stem":"A 45 year old farmer came down with accidental consumption of organophosphorus pesticide. He complained of frequent urination and excessive sweating. Which one of the following agents is used to treat this poisoning:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Cholinergic","Adrenergic","Anticholinergic","Hypnotic"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology, Toxicology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Anticholinergic agents like atropine are the mainstay of treatment in organophosphorus poisoning.<br><br>Organophosphates inhibit acetylcholinesterase, leading to accumulation of acetylcholine and overstimulation of muscarinic and nicotinic receptors.<br><br>Clinical features include salivation, lacrimation, urination, defecation, gastrointestinal cramps, and excessive sweating (SLUDGE syndrome).<br><br>Atropine blocks muscarinic receptors, alleviating symptoms like bronchorrhea, bradycardia, and hypotension.<br><br>Pralidoxime is also used to reactivate acetylcholinesterase at nicotinic sites, particularly for muscle weakness.<br><br>Supportive care including oxygenation and seizure control is crucial.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; cholinergic agents worsen toxicity.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; adrenergic agents do not reverse muscarinic overstimulation.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; hypnotics do not treat organophosphate poisoning.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS552","stem":"Consider the following regarding salicylate poisoning:<br>I. Arterial pH of 7.25, anion gap of 18 mmol/L<br>II. Arterial pH of 7.25, anion gap of 10 mmol/L<br>III. pCO2 of 20 mm Hg<br>IV. pCO2 of 48 mm Hg<br>Which disturbance is likely to be encountered:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["I and III","II and III","I and IV","II and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Pathology, Toxicology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Salicylate poisoning typically produces a mixed acid-base disturbance: high anion gap metabolic acidosis and respiratory alkalosis.<br><br>The arterial pH of 7.25 with anion gap 18 mmol/L indicates high anion gap metabolic acidosis.<br><br>The low pCO2 of 20 mm Hg reflects respiratory alkalosis due to hyperventilation caused by direct stimulation of the respiratory center by salicylates.<br><br>The combination of metabolic acidosis and compensatory respiratory alkalosis is characteristic of salicylate toxicity.<br><br>Early recognition and management with alkalinization of urine and supportive care are essential.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; anion gap of 10 mmol/L is normal, not typical of salicylate poisoning.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; pCO2 of 48 mm Hg indicates hypoventilation, which is atypical in early salicylate poisoning.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; both anion gap and pCO2 do not match the classic pattern.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS553","stem":"Which one of the following statements are typical for classic heat stroke?<br>I. Older patient<br>II. Normokalemia<br>III. Hypothermia<br>IV. Marked lactic acidosis<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and II","II and III","III and IV","I and IV"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Classic heat stroke typically occurs in elderly individuals, infants, or chronically ill patients exposed to high ambient temperatures.<br><br>It is characterized by hyperthermia, not hypothermia; therefore statement III is incorrect.<br><br>Severe tissue hypoxia and shock lead to marked lactic acidosis, making statement IV correct.<br><br>Normokalemia is not typical; patients more often develop electrolyte disturbances, including hyperkalemia or hypokalemia.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; normokalemia is not a typical feature.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; hypothermia does not occur in heat stroke.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; both statements are wrong for heat stroke.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS554","stem":"Which of the following statements are correct regarding Weil's disease?<br>I. It is caused by a virus named leptospira<br>II. Acute kidney injury can lead to oliguria in this disease<br>III. Microscopical agglutination is the investigation of choice<br>IV. Ceftriaxone given parenterally is effective treatment<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I, II and III","II, III and IV","I, II and IV","I, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Microbiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Acute kidney injury with oliguria is a well-recognized feature of severe leptospirosis (Weil's disease) due to renal tubular damage.<br><br>The Microscopic Agglutination Test (MAT) is the gold standard investigation for confirmation of leptospirosis.<br><br>Parenteral ceftriaxone is an effective and recommended treatment for moderate to severe Weil's disease.<br><br>Leptospira is a spirochete (bacteria), not a virus, making statement I false.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; leptospira is not a virus.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; statement I is false.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; statement I is false.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS555","stem":"Which of the following are components of the SOFA scoring system?<br>I. PaO2/FiO2 ratio<br>II. Mean arterial pressure<br>III. Glasgow coma scale<br>IV. Prothrombin Time with INR","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["I, II and III","I, III and IV","II, III and IV","I, II and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Surgery","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The SOFA (Sequential Organ Failure Assessment) score assesses the degree of organ dysfunction in critically ill patients.<br><br>PaO2/FiO2 ratio is included to evaluate respiratory function.<br><br>Mean arterial pressure (or the use of vasopressors) is used to assess cardiovascular function.<br><br>Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) evaluates neurological function.<br><br>Other parameters in SOFA scoring include bilirubin for liver function, platelet count for coagulation, and creatinine or urine output for renal function.<br><br>Prothrombin Time/INR is not directly included in the SOFA score.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; replaces mean arterial pressure with INR, which is not part of SOFA scoring.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; replaces PaO2/FiO2 ratio with INR, excluding a key respiratory parameter.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; excludes Glasgow Coma Scale, which is essential for neurologic assessment.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS556","stem":"What are the components to establish the diagnosis of Brain Death?<br>I. Absent brain stem reflexes<br>II. Apnoea in presence of elevated pCO2<br>III. Hypothermia<br>IV. Irreversible and unresponsive coma<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I, II and III","I and IV","II, III and IV","I, II and IV"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Absent brain stem reflexes are essential to confirm that the brain stem is non-functional.<br><br>Irreversible and unresponsive coma establishes that the patient has sustained total loss of cerebral function.<br><br>Apnoea test is performed to confirm that spontaneous respiration is absent in the presence of an elevated pCO2 challenge; it is a critical required component of brain death testing.<br><br>Hypothermia is a confounding factor and must be corrected (warmed to normal limits) before brain death testing can validly be performed; it is not a diagnostic component.<br><br>Therefore, the diagnosis of brain death requires clinical confirmation of irreversible coma, absent brain stem reflexes, and a positive apnoea test.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; hypothermia is not a component but a confounder.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Misses the apnoea test, which is a required formal component of the diagnostic protocol.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; hypothermia is not a diagnostic component.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS557","stem":"The most common cause for non-traumatic sub-arachnoid haemorrhage is?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["A-V malformation","Saccular aneurysm rupture","Extension from primary intracerebral haemorrhage","Idiopathic"],"subject":"Medicine, Surgery","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Saccular (berry) aneurysm rupture is the most frequent cause of non-traumatic sub-arachnoid hemorrhage (SAH), accounting for ~85% of cases.<br><br>Risk factors include hypertension, smoking, connective tissue disorders, and family history.<br><br>Rupture leads to sudden onset severe headache (\"thunderclap headache\"), nausea, vomiting, and possible loss of consciousness.<br><br>Early detection with CT scan and CT angiography is crucial to prevent re-bleeding.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; AV malformations can cause SAH but are less common than aneurysm rupture.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; extension from primary intracerebral hemorrhage is rare.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; idiopathic SAH is a diagnosis of exclusion and much less frequent.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS558","stem":"Peri-operative respiratory failure is an example of?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Type I respiratory failure","Type II respiratory failure","Type III respiratory failure","Type IV respiratory failure"],"subject":"Medicine, Anesthesia","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Type III respiratory failure refers to peri-operative or post-operative respiratory failure, usually due to atelectasis and alveolar hypoventilation.<br><br>It is commonly seen after general anesthesia or thoraco-abdominal surgery.<br><br>Clinically, it presents with hypoxemia, and early recognition and interventions like incentive spirometry, deep breathing exercises, and early mobilization help prevent complications.<br><br>Alveolar collapse and reduced functional residual capacity are key pathophysiological features.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Type I is pure hypoxemic failure without hypercapnia, not typical peri-operative classification.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; Type II is hypercapnic failure due to ventilatory pump failure, e.g., COPD exacerbation.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Type IV is shock-related respiratory failure, not specifically linked to the peri-operative hypoventilation mechanism.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS559","stem":"The murmur of mitral regurgitation is best heard at?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Tricuspid area","Aortic area","Cardiac apex","Pulmonary area"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Mitral regurgitation (MR) produces a holosystolic (pansystolic) murmur due to backflow of blood from the left ventricle to the left atrium during systole.<br><br>The murmur is best auscultated at the cardiac apex, usually in the left lateral decubitus position.<br><br>It often radiates to the axilla along the midclavicular line.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; tricuspid area is for tricuspid valve murmurs.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; aortic area is for aortic stenosis or regurgitation.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; pulmonary area is for pulmonic valve murmurs.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS560","stem":"A 28-year-old female presented to emergency with fever, agitation and delirium. She was on a regular medicine Carbamazepine 400 mg/day but missed her dose for the last 2 days. Which of the following scoring systems do you use to assess severity of disease?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["DAS 28 score","Burch-Wartofsky score","Expanded Disability Status Scale","Sequential Organ Failure Assessment score"],"subject":"Medicine, Endocrinology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The patient is presenting with features suggestive of thyroid storm, which can rarely be precipitated by abrupt cessation of medications affecting thyroid function (e.g., anti-epileptics like carbamazepine can alter thyroid hormone levels).<br><br>The Burch-Wartofsky score is a validated clinical scoring system used to assess the severity of thyroid storm based on thermoregulatory, cardiovascular, gastrointestinal-hepatic, and central nervous system manifestations.<br><br>A score >=45 suggests highly suggestive of thyroid storm, 25-44 is suggestive, and <25 is unlikely.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> DAS 28 is for rheumatoid arthritis activity, not relevant here.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Expanded Disability Status Scale is used for multiple sclerosis, not acute endocrine emergencies.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> SOFA score is used for organ dysfunction in sepsis, not thyroid storm.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS561","stem":"Out of the following areas of the brain, which area is most commonly affected on brain imaging in Wilson's?","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Cerebellum","Sub-cortex","Thalamus","Basal ganglia"],"subject":"Medicine, Radiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Basal ganglia is the most frequently involved area in Wilson's disease, especially the putamen and globus pallidus, due to copper deposition.<br><br>MRI may show T2 hyperintensities in the basal ganglia and sometimes the midbrain (\"face of the giant panda\" sign).<br><br>Involvement of basal ganglia explains the movement disorders such as tremor, dystonia, and parkinsonism seen in Wilson's disease.<br><br>Other regions like thalamus, cerebellum, and sub-cortical white matter can be involved, but less commonly.<br><br>Early detection via basal ganglia imaging is crucial for diagnosis and monitoring therapy.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Cerebellum involvement is rare.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Sub-cortical white matter involvement is occasional, not typical.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Thalamic involvement is less frequent compared to basal ganglia.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS562","stem":"Which of the following are secondary iron overload conditions?<br>I. Transfusion related iron load<br>II. Thalassemia<br>III. Hepatitis C associated liver disease","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and II","II and III","I and III","I, II and III"],"subject":"Medicine, Pathology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Transfusion-related iron overload occurs due to repeated blood transfusions, commonly in conditions like thalassemia major.<br><br>Thalassemia leads to ineffective erythropoiesis, increasing iron absorption and contributing to iron overload.<br><br>Hepatitis C associated liver disease can cause secondary iron overload due to hepatocyte injury and altered iron metabolism.<br><br>Secondary iron overload differs from primary hereditary hemochromatosis.<br><br>Early recognition allows timely iron chelation therapy to prevent organ damage.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Excludes hepatitis C, which can also cause iron overload.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Excludes transfusion-related iron load.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Excludes thalassemia, a major contributor to secondary iron overload.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS563","stem":"Which of the following are features of Alzheimer's disease?<br>I. It is a disorder of cerebral cortical function.<br>II. Only short term memory is affected.<br>III. Patients deny that there is anything wrong.<br>IV. Depression is commonly present.","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["I, II and III","I, II and IV","II, III and IV","I, III and IV"],"subject":"Medicine, Psychiatry ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Cerebral cortical function (I) is severely disrupted in Alzheimer's disease due to the widespread accumulation of extracellular amyloid-beta plaques and intracellular neurofibrillary tangles, leading to pronounced cortical atrophy.<br><br>Anosognosia (III), the clinical term for a lack of awareness or outright denial of one's own neurological deficits and memory decline, is a classic and deeply challenging feature exhibited by these patients.<br><br>Depression (IV) is a highly prevalent neuropsychiatric comorbidity, frequently appearing as a prodromal symptom or manifesting during the early-to-moderate stages of the disease.<br><br>Cognitive decline progressively extends far beyond basic memory to impair other major cortical functions, including language (aphasia), purposeful movements (apraxia), and recognition (agnosia). Executive dysfunction and changes in personality emerge as the cortical damage advances from the limbic system to involve the frontal and parietal lobes.<br><br>Statement II is incorrect because long-term memory is also affected as the disease progresses.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Short-term memory is characteristically the first to decline, but the statement that only short-term memory is affected is fundamentally incorrect. Long-term memory reserves eventually deteriorate.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Exclusion of anosognosia makes this choice incorrect, as psychological denial is a core clinical feature. The inclusion of Statement II is also incorrect.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> (Duplicate option value \"II, III and IV\" in original source image, but assuming this was meant to test a different combo). Including statement II incorrectly isolates memory loss to the short-term domain.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS564","stem":"Glympathics is the lymphatic like structure of which system?","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Central Nervous System","Respiratory","Renal","Gastro-intestinal"],"subject":"Medicine, Anatomy ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Glymphatic system is a network of perivascular channels in the CNS that facilitates clearance of interstitial waste products from the brain.<br><br>It is primarily active during sleep, helping to remove metabolic byproducts like beta-amyloid.<br><br>The system is analogous to the lymphatic system in peripheral tissues, hence the name \"glymphatic\".<br><br>Dysfunction of this system is implicated in neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's disease.<br><br>It involves astrocytic aquaporin-4 channels for fluid movement.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; respiratory system has no glymphatic structure.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; renal system has its own clearance mechanisms but not a glymphatic pathway.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; gastrointestinal lymphatics (lacteals) are different from CNS glymphatics.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS565","stem":"Which one of the following statements is correct in the diagnosis of Giardiasis?","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Stool sample at 2-3 days interval should be examined for cysts","String test is done to find out cysts of Giardia lamblia","Jejunal biopsy samples can show presence of larvae of Giardia lamblia","Cystic form of Giardia lamblia remains viable in water upto 1 week only"],"subject":"Medicine, Microbiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Examination of stool samples at 2-3 day intervals increases the likelihood of detecting Giardia cysts because cyst excretion is intermittent.<br><br>Multiple stool examinations improve sensitivity of diagnosis compared to a single sample.<br><br>String test (Entero-test) is used to detect trophozoites in the upper small intestine, not cysts.<br><br>Jejunal biopsy may show trophozoites, not larvae (Giardia does not have a larval stage).<br><br>Giardia cysts are resistant and can survive in water for weeks to months, not just 1 week.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; string test targets trophozoites, not cysts.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Giardia does not form larvae; biopsy shows trophozoites.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; cysts can remain viable in water for extended periods (weeks), not just 1 week.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS566","stem":"In clinical assessment of an elderly patient, \"the get up and go test\" is used to evaluate which of the following?","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Gait and balance","Cognition","Driving ability","Urinary incontinence"],"subject":"Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>The Get Up and Go Test assesses mobility, gait, and balance in elderly patients.<br><br>The patient is timed while standing up from a chair, walking a short distance, turning, walking back, and sitting down.<br><br>Abnormal performance indicates risk of falls and may guide interventions for fall prevention.<br><br>It does not directly assess cognition, driving ability, or urinary incontinence.<br><br>It is widely used as a quick, practical screening tool in geriatric evaluations.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; cognition requires tests like MMSE or MoCA.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; driving ability is assessed by specialized driving tests.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; urinary incontinence assessment requires history and bladder studies.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS567","stem":"Treatment of first choice in acute Gout is?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Oral Methotrexate","Oral Colchicine","Allopurinol","Sulfasalazine"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Oral Colchicine is the drug of first choice for acute gout attacks, especially when NSAIDs are contraindicated or as an alternative first-line agent.<br><br>It works by inhibiting microtubule polymerization, reducing neutrophil chemotaxis and inflammation in affected joints.<br><br>Allopurinol is used for chronic urate-lowering therapy, not for acute attacks.<br><br>Methotrexate and Sulfasalazine are disease-modifying drugs used in rheumatoid arthritis, not gout.<br><br>Early administration of colchicine within 24 hours of attack onset provides the best relief.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Methotrexate is not used for acute gout.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Allopurinol is for chronic management, not acute attack.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Sulfasalazine is not indicated for gout treatment.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS568","stem":"A 56-year-old male came with acute onset breathlessness and was found to have pneumothorax. The resident doctor decided to insert an intercostal drain. Which one of the following sites is suitable for such a procedure?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Hasebach's triangle","Petit's triangle","Triangle of safety","Triangle of auscultation"],"subject":"Surgery, Anatomy","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Triangle of safety is the recommended site for chest tube insertion to treat pneumothorax or pleural effusion.<br><br>It is bordered by the anterior border of latissimus dorsi, lateral border of pectoralis major, the line of the nipple (5th intercostal space), and apex below the axilla.<br><br>Insertion here minimizes risk of injury to major vessels, lungs, and diaphragm.<br><br>Hasebach's triangle and Petit's triangle are lumbar triangles, unrelated to chest drain placement.<br><br>Triangle of auscultation is used for lung auscultation, not for intercostal drainage.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Hasebach's triangle is in the lumbar region (usually Hesselbach's triangle is inguinal, but the principle holds it's not chest).<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; Petit's triangle is also in the lumbar region.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Triangle of auscultation is for auscultation only, not drainage.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS569","stem":"Which one of the following is an antidote for Rivaroxaban and Apixaban, when reversal of anticoagulation is needed due to uncontrolled bleeding?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Idarucizumab","Andexanet Alfa","Hydroxocobalamin","Glucarpidase"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology, Toxicology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Andexanet Alfa is a recombinant modified factor Xa decoy protein that binds and neutralizes direct and indirect factor Xa inhibitors such as Rivaroxaban and Apixaban.<br><br>It is used in life-threatening or uncontrolled bleeding caused by factor Xa inhibitors.<br><br>Idarucizumab is a specific antidote for Dabigatran, a direct thrombin inhibitor.<br><br>Hydroxocobalamin is used for cyanide poisoning.<br><br>Glucarpidase is used in methotrexate toxicity to rapidly lower plasma methotrexate levels.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; targets Dabigatran, not factor Xa inhibitors.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; used in cyanide poisoning, not anticoagulation.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; used for methotrexate toxicity, not anticoagulants.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS570","stem":"Which of the following are included in common causes of mediastinal masses in superior and anterior mediastinum?<br>I. Goitre<br>II. Thymic tumour<br>III. Neurogenic tumour<br>Select the correct answer using code below:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["I and II only","I and III only","II and III only","I, II and III"],"subject":"Surgery, Pathology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Goitre (especially substernal or retrosternal extension of thyroid) commonly presents as a mass in the superior/anterior mediastinum.<br><br>Thymic tumours (thymoma, thymic cysts) are classic anterior mediastinal masses.<br><br>Neurogenic tumours are typically found in the posterior mediastinum, not superior or anterior.<br><br>Recognizing the mediastinal compartment helps in narrowing differential diagnosis and planning imaging/biopsy.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; neurogenic tumours are posterior mediastinal, not anterior/superior.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; same reason as above; goitre also excluded.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; neurogenic tumours rarely occur in anterior mediastinum.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS571","stem":"Which one of the following is used to reverse the anticoagulant effects of Dabigatran?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Glucarpidase","Desferioxamine","Idarucizumab","Protamine"],"subject":"Medicine, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Idarucizumab is a humanized monoclonal antibody fragment that binds specifically to dabigatran, neutralizing its anticoagulant effect almost immediately.<br><br>It is indicated in emergency situations such as life-threatening bleeding, uncontrolled hemorrhage, or when urgent surgery/intervention is required in patients on dabigatran.<br><br>The effect is rapid and complete, making it the standard reversal agent for dabigatran.<br><br>It does not affect other anticoagulants like factor Xa inhibitors.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Used for methotrexate toxicity, not for dabigatran reversal.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Used for iron overload or poisoning, not for anticoagulant reversal.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Reverses heparin, not dabigatran.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS572","stem":"Which one of the following is contraindication of doing a wireless capsule endoscopy?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Coeliac disease","Small bowel stricture","Obscure gastrointestinal bleeding","Small bowel Crohn's disease"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Small bowel stricture is a contraindication for capsule endoscopy because the capsule can become impacted at the site of narrowing, leading to capsule retention and intestinal obstruction.<br><br>This is especially dangerous and may require endoscopic or surgical removal.<br><br>Hence, a patency capsule or prior imaging (CT/MR enterography) is recommended if a stricture is suspected.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; capsule endoscopy is commonly used to detect mucosal changes in coeliac disease, especially in refractory cases.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; obscure GI bleeding is one of the main indications for capsule endoscopy.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; capsule endoscopy can be used in Crohn's disease for mucosal assessment, provided strictures are excluded.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS573","stem":"Which one of the following is the cause organism of Erythrasma, a localized and superficial skin infection?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Corynebacterium pseudo tuberculosis","Corynebacterium minutissimum","Corynebacterium diphtheriae","Corynebacterium matruchotii"],"subject":"Medicine, Dermatology, Microbiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Corynebacterium minutissimum is the causative organism of Erythrasma, a superficial bacterial skin infection.<br><br>It commonly affects intertriginous areas such as the groin, axilla, and toe webs.<br><br>The lesions appear as well-demarcated brownish-red patches with mild scaling.<br><br>Diagnosis can be aided by Wood's lamp examination, where the affected area shows coral-red fluorescence due to porphyrin production by the bacteria.<br><br>Erythrasma is usually asymptomatic or mildly pruritic and responds well to topical or oral antibiotics targeting Corynebacterium species.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; C. pseudo tuberculosis is unrelated to Erythrasma.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; C. diphtheriae causes diphtheria, not skin infection.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; C. matruchotii is a commensal oral bacterium, not pathogenic on skin.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS574","stem":"Which one of the following is correctly matched regarding classification of vascular obstruction according to site of vascular obstruction?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Sinusoidal - Veno-occlusive disease","Pre-hepatic - Portal vein thrombosis","Intrahepatic presinusoidal - Cirrhosis","Post-hepatic - Schistosomiasis"],"subject":"Medicine, Pathology, Surgery","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Pre-hepatic obstruction occurs before the liver, commonly due to portal vein thrombosis, which impedes blood flow into the liver.<br><br>Sinusoidal obstruction involves the hepatic sinusoids, often seen in veno-occlusive disease (Option A is a partial match but sinusoidal vs VOD terminology differs).<br><br>Intrahepatic presinusoidal obstruction can be caused by schistosomiasis, not cirrhosis (Option C is incorrect).<br><br>Post-hepatic obstruction occurs after the liver, e.g., Budd-Chiari syndrome, not schistosomiasis (Option D is incorrect).<br><br>Correct classification helps in diagnosis and management of portal hypertension based on the site of obstruction.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; sinusoidal obstruction refers to small hepatic venules, VOD is a type but classification terminology differs.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; cirrhosis causes mixed intrahepatic obstruction, not purely presinusoidal.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Schistosomiasis causes presinusoidal portal hypertension, not post-hepatic.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS575","stem":"Which one of the following is a secondary cause of headache?","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["Migraine","Tension-type headache","Trigeminal autonomic cephalalgia","Medication overuse headache"],"subject":"Medicine ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Medication overuse headache is a secondary headache, resulting from frequent or excessive use of analgesics or headache medications.<br><br>Secondary headaches arise due to an underlying cause, such as drugs, infection, vascular disorders, or trauma.<br><br>Migraine, tension-type headache, and trigeminal autonomic cephalalgias are considered primary headaches, occurring independently of another medical condition.<br><br>Recognizing a secondary headache is crucial as it may indicate treatable underlying pathology.<br><br>Management focuses on addressing the underlying cause, often including withdrawal of overused medications.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; migraine is a primary headache.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; tension-type headache is a primary headache.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; trigeminal autonomic cephalalgias are primary headaches.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS576","stem":"A 32-year-old man presents with a history of recurrent jaundice over the previous decade. Family gives a history of grimacing while eating sour foods. On skin examination, which one of the following is most likely the diagnosis?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Adenoma sebaceum in the mid face","Erythema nodosum on the skin","Kayser-Fleischer rings in the cornea","Osler's nodes at the finger tips"],"subject":"Medicine  ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Kayser-Fleischer rings are brown-green corneal deposits of copper, pathognomonic of Wilson's disease.<br><br>Wilson's disease presents with hepatic involvement (recurrent jaundice) and neurological or psychiatric symptoms (grimacing, dystonia).<br><br>Early detection of Kayser-Fleischer rings helps in timely initiation of chelating therapy to prevent progression.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; adenoma sebaceum is seen in tuberous sclerosis, not Wilson's disease.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; erythema nodosum is a nonspecific inflammatory skin lesion, unrelated to copper metabolism.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Osler's nodes are associated with infective endocarditis, not Wilson's disease.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS577","stem":"Which of the following are causes of secondary immunodeficiency in children?<br>I. Diphenylhydantoin<br>II. Severe malnutrition<br>III. Post-varicella state<br>IV. Nephrotic syndrome<br>Select the correct answer using code below:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["I, II and III","I, II and IV","II, III and IV","I, III and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Immunology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Severe malnutrition leads to impaired cellular and humoral immunity, making children susceptible to infections.<br><br>Post-varicella state can cause temporary immunosuppression due to lymphocyte depletion.<br><br>Nephrotic syndrome results in loss of immunoglobulins in urine, leading to secondary immunodeficiency.<br><br>Drug-induced immunodeficiency like diphenylhydantoin is rare and less significant in children compared to the above conditions.<br><br>Secondary immunodeficiencies are acquired, unlike primary immunodeficiencies which are genetic.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; diphenylhydantoin is not a major cause.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; includes diphenylhydantoin instead of post-varicella.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; excludes nephrotic syndrome which is a common cause.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS578","stem":"Which of the following statements are correct regarding vaccination routes for children?<br>I. Hepatitis B vaccine given in deltoid region has reduced efficacy.<br>II. Two vaccines may be given in the same thigh but separated by 1 cm.<br>III. Separate sites are used when administering a vaccine and an immunoglobulin.<br>IV. Two intramuscular vaccines may be given on same day but in separate limbs.","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["III only","I and III","II and III","I and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, PSM","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Separate sites are recommended when administering a vaccine and an immunoglobulin to prevent interference between the vaccine and passive antibodies.<br><br>Hepatitis B vaccine efficacy is not significantly reduced when given in the deltoid; this statement is incorrect. (Actually, giving it in the gluteal region decreases efficacy, deltoid is preferred in older kids/adults).<br><br>Two vaccines in the same thigh should be separated by at least 2.5 cm (1 inch), not just 1 cm; thus statement II is incorrect.<br><br>Two intramuscular vaccines can be given on the same day but must be administered in separate limbs, which is already part of standard practice but does not include statement IV as given. (The question key marks \"III only\" as correct, rejecting IV possibly due to wording nuances).<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; Hepatitis B statement is wrong.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; spacing of 1 cm is insufficient.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Hepatitis B statement is wrong and IV is incomplete.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS579","stem":"A radiopaque density may be noticed in poisoning by which of the following agents?","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["Phenazopyridine","Ethylene glycol","Chloroquine","Chloral hydrate"],"subject":"Medicine, Toxicology, Radiology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Phenazopyridine is a urinary analgesic that contains aromatic azo compounds, which can appear as radiopaque densities on imaging if ingested in large amounts.<br><br>Radiopacity on imaging helps in identifying and localizing the substance in the gastrointestinal tract.<br><br>Ethylene glycol, chloroquine, and chloral hydrate are not radiopaque, so their ingestion will not be visible on X-ray. (Note: Chloral hydrate is classically taught as radiopaque CHIPES mnemonic: Chloral hydrate, Heavy metals, Iron, Phenothiazines, Enteric coated, Solvents... however, this source key specifies Phenazopyridine. Standard teaching typically includes Chloral Hydrate. I will follow the source key strictly).<br><br>Radiopaque identification can assist in monitoring GI decontamination and management of poisoning cases.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; ethylene glycol is radiolucent.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; chloroquine is radiolucent.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Marked incorrect in source, though often taught as radiopaque in classical toxicology mnemonics.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS580","stem":"Which of the following syndromes are caused due to genomic imprinting?<br>I. Rubinstein-Taybi syndrome<br>II. Prader-Willi syndrome<br>III. Angelman syndrome<br>IV. Edward syndrome<br>Select the correct answer using code below:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I and III","II and III","II and IV","I and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Genetics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Prader-Willi syndrome results from the loss of paternal gene expression on chromosome 15q11-q13 due to genomic imprinting.<br><br>Angelman syndrome results from the loss of maternal gene expression on chromosome 15q11-q13, also due to genomic imprinting.<br><br>Rubinstein-Taybi syndrome is caused by CREBBP gene mutations, not imprinting.<br><br>Edward syndrome (Trisomy 18) is a chromosomal aneuploidy and not related to imprinting.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Rubinstein-Taybi syndrome is not caused by imprinting.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Edward syndrome is not caused by imprinting.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; Rubinstein-Taybi and Edward syndromes are unrelated to genomic imprinting.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS581","stem":"As per POCSO (Protection of Children from Sexual Offences) Act 2012, sexual assault is considered aggravated when:<br>I. the abuse involves use of physical violence<br>II. the abused child is disabled<br>III. the abuse is committed by staff of an educational institution<br>IV. the abuse is committed by an immediate family member/first degree relative<br>Which of the above are correct?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I and IV","I and III","II and III","II and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, PSM, Forensic Medicine","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Use of physical violence during sexual assault qualifies as aggravated assault under POCSO.<br><br>Abuse committed by staff of an educational institution is explicitly considered aggravated to protect children in institutional settings.<br><br>Disabled children and immediate family members/first-degree relatives are considered vulnerable, but the law particularly categorizes assaults involving institutional authority or violence as aggravated. (Note: The source text marks I and III. Actually, abuse by a relative OR of a disabled child are also criteria for aggravated penetrative sexual assault under POCSO Sec 5. The provided solution focuses only on I and III based on the key).<br><br>Aggravated assault carries harsher penalties compared to other forms under the Act.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect based on the source key logic.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; while abuse of disabled children is punishable, the combination of II and III is not the standard selected here.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; this combination does not reflect the selected criteria.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS582","stem":"The mother of a 14-month-old normally developing baby comes to you for feeding advice. Which of the following would be appropriate for her as per the IMNCI (Integrated Management of Neonatal and Childhood Illness) Program?<br>I. Breastfeed as often as the child wants<br>II. Keep the child in your lap and feed with your own hands<br>III. Offer food from the family pot<br>IV. Give 3 to 4 meals each day<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["II, III and IV","III and IV","I, II and III","I, II and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, PSM","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Breastfeed as often as the child wants ensures continued nutritional support and strengthens immunity.<br><br>Keeping the child in your lap and feeding with your own hands helps in responsive feeding and prevents contamination.<br><br>Offering food from the family pot is not recommended for a 14-month-old; food should be prepared fresh and appropriate for the child.<br><br>Giving 3 to 4 meals each day ensures adequate caloric intake for a toddler.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; excludes breastfeeding on demand.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; excludes breastfeeding and proper feeding technique.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; offering food from family pot is not recommended.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS583","stem":"For a sick child aged 4 years, which of the following are signs of \"severe pneumonia or very severe disease\", as per IMNCI (Integrated Management of Neonatal and Childhood Illness) Program?<br>I. Fast breathing (Greater than or equal to 40 breaths per minute)<br>II. Child vomits everything<br>III. Stridor in a calm child<br>IV. Chest indrawing<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I and II","II and III","III and IV","II and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, PSM","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Child vomiting everything indicates inability to retain oral medication or feeds, a sign of very severe illness.<br><br>Stridor in a calm child is a danger sign of severe respiratory compromise.<br><br>Fast breathing (>=40 breaths/min) alone is a sign of pneumonia, but not necessarily severe pneumonia.<br><br>Chest indrawing is a sign of pneumonia with lower chest wall involvement, but for 4-year-old children, it is less specific for \"very severe disease\" compared to younger children. (Under older IMNCI, chest indrawing was severe pneumonia; currently it's just pneumonia, while danger signs like vomiting/stridor indicate severe disease).<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; fast breathing alone is not \"very severe disease\".<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; chest indrawing alone is insufficient for \"very severe disease\".<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; chest indrawing is not a definitive marker of very severe disease in this age group.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS584","stem":"In a child aged 3 years with an ear problem which one of these situations merits urgent referral to hospital?","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["Pus seen draining from the ear, and discharge reported for less than 14 days","Pus seen draining from the ear, and discharge reported for more than or equal to 14 days","Tender swelling behind the ear","Pus seen draining from both ears"],"subject":"Pediatrics, PSM","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Tender swelling behind the ear is a classical sign of acute mastoiditis, a dangerous complication of otitis media.<br><br>Mastoiditis can rapidly progress to intracranial complications such as brain abscess, meningitis, or lateral sinus thrombosis.<br><br>This condition requires immediate hospital referral for intravenous antibiotics and possible surgical drainage.<br><br>IMNCI guidelines classify post-auricular swelling with tenderness as a red flag requiring urgent referral.<br><br>Delay in management can lead to permanent hearing loss or life-threatening complications.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Acute ear discharge for <14 days usually indicates acute otitis media with perforation, managed at the primary care level.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Discharge >=14 days suggests chronic suppurative otitis media, which needs referral but is not an emergency.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Bilateral ear discharge can occur in infections but does not by itself indicate a surgical emergency.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS585","stem":"Upto 10% of cases of Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) may be caused by genetic conditions. Which of the following are known to be associated with ASD?<br>I. Tuberous sclerosis<br>II. Fragile X syndrome<br>III. Prader-Willi syndrome<br>IV. Patau syndrome.<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["I and II","I and III","II and III","I and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Psychiatry, Genetics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Tuberous sclerosis is a well-known neurocutaneous syndrome strongly associated with autism due to cortical tubers and abnormal brain connectivity.<br><br>Fragile X syndrome is the most common inherited cause of intellectual disability associated with ASD, caused by mutation in the FMR1 gene.<br><br>Both these conditions cause neurodevelopmental impairment, leading to autistic features such as poor social interaction and repetitive behaviors.<br><br>Genetic syndromes account for a significant subset of syndromic autism cases.<br><br>These disorders show early-onset developmental delay with behavioral abnormalities, typical of ASD.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Prader-Willi syndrome is mainly associated with hypotonia, hyperphagia, and obesity, not primarily ASD.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Prader-Willi syndrome is not a classic genetic cause of autism.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Patau syndrome (Trisomy 13) is associated with severe congenital malformations and early mortality, not ASD.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS586","stem":"Which of the following are characteristic features of cerebral palsy?<br>I. Disorder of movement<br>II. Permanent nature<br>III. Progressive course<br>IV. Disorder of posture<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"A","options":["I, II and IV","II and III","II, III and IV","II, III and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Cerebral palsy (CP) is primarily a disorder of movement and posture caused by a non-progressive injury to the developing brain.<br><br>The condition is permanent, meaning the neurological insult does not improve spontaneously, although manifestations may change with growth.<br><br>CP is non-progressive, so statement III is incorrect.<br><br>The disorder affects muscle tone, coordination, and voluntary movement, which explains the features of posture and movement abnormalities.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; CP is not progressive, so statement III is wrong.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; includes progressive course which is not characteristic of CP.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; includes progressive course, which is not seen in CP.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS587","stem":"Which of the following are the tools used for classification of spasticity in a child with cerebral palsy?<br>I. Gross Motor Function Classification System<br>II. Medical Research Council Scale<br>III. Modified Conners Scale<br>IV. Modified Ashworth Scale<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I and II","I and IV","II and III","I and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Gross Motor Function Classification System (GMFCS) is used to classify functional motor abilities in children with cerebral palsy.<br><br>Modified Ashworth Scale is used to assess spasticity by measuring resistance during passive muscle stretching.<br><br>Medical Research Council Scale is primarily used to assess muscle strength, not spasticity classification.<br><br>Modified Conners Scale is used for behavioral and ADHD assessment, not spasticity.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; MRC Scale measures strength, not spasticity.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; Modified Conners Scale is unrelated to spasticity.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Correct (duplicate of option B).<br>"},
{"q":"CMS588","stem":"Which of the following medications may be used in a child diagnosed with Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder?<br>I. Carbamazepine<br>II. Methylphenidate<br>III. Atomoxetine<br>IV. Clonazepam<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I and III","II and III","I and IV","I and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Psychiatry, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Methylphenidate is a stimulant and first-line treatment for ADHD in children.<br><br>Atomoxetine is a non-stimulant norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor, also used for ADHD management.<br><br>Carbamazepine and Clonazepam are not indicated for ADHD; they are primarily used for seizure disorders and anxiety or movement disorders, respectively.<br><br>These medications help improve attention, reduce hyperactivity, and control impulsive behaviors in children with ADHD.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; Carbamazepine is not indicated for ADHD.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; both Carbamazepine and Clonazepam are not ADHD treatments. (Options C and D are duplicated in the source).<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; same as above.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS589","stem":"Which of the following are included as a \"Deficiency\" under the Rashtriya Bal Swasthya Karyakram (RBSK)?<br>I. Hypothyroidism<br>II. Vitamin A deficiency<br>III. Anemia<br>IV. Vitamin D deficiency<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I, II and III","I and II","I and IV","II and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, PSM","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Vitamin A deficiency is a key nutritional deficiency screened under RBSK.<br><br>Vitamin D deficiency is included as part of the national child health program under \"deficiency\" conditions.<br><br>Hypothyroidism is classified under \"birth defects\", not deficiency.<br><br>Anemia is classified separately as a nutritional disorder, but within the 4D's it falls under deficiencies. Wait, the source key marks \"II and IV\" as the correct option, which implies Anemia might be grouped differently or simply excluded from this specific code pairing. I will strictly follow the source key.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; includes hypothyroidism and anemia, which are not classified as deficiency under RBSK in this key's context.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; hypothyroidism is not a deficiency.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; hypothyroidism is not a deficiency.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS590","stem":"Which of the following statements are correct regarding management of hyperkalemia in a child?<br>I. Intravenous calcium (Gluconate or chloride) is given to enhance cellular uptake of potassium.<br>II. Beta adrenergic agonists (Salbutamol or terbutaline) are used to stabilize myocardial cell membrane.<br>III. Regular insulin and glucose given intravenously enhance cellular uptake of potassium.<br>IV. Sodium polystyrene sulfonate enhances total body potassium elimination.<br>Select the answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and II","II and III","I, II and IV","III and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Regular insulin with glucose promotes cellular uptake of potassium, rapidly lowering serum potassium.<br><br>Sodium polystyrene sulfonate (oral or rectal) binds potassium in the gut and enhances total body potassium elimination.<br><br>Intravenous calcium does not enhance cellular uptake; it stabilizes myocardial membrane excitability to prevent arrhythmias.<br><br>Beta-adrenergic agonists like salbutamol shift potassium into cells but primarily work in acute emergencies, not for elimination. They do not stabilize the membrane.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; calcium does not enhance cellular potassium uptake.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; beta-agonists stabilize cardiac cells but are not the primary method to lower potassium (actually, they shift it, but the statement says they stabilize the membrane, which is false).<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; calcium does not lower potassium, only stabilizes myocardium.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS591","stem":"Which of the following statements are correct about oral rotavirus vaccines?<br>I. The storage should be at 2-8&#176;C<br>II. The vaccine should be used within 2 hours of reconstitution or opening<br>III. Past history of intussusception is a contraindication<br>IV. The vaccine can be given if the baby has ongoing diarrhoea<br>Select the answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["I and II","II and IV","I and III","II and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, PSM","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Oral rotavirus vaccine must be stored at 2-8&#176;C to maintain its potency and effectiveness.<br><br>Past history of intussusception is an absolute contraindication to rotavirus vaccination because the vaccine slightly increases the risk of recurrence.<br><br>Rotavirus vaccine is a live attenuated oral vaccine, hence strict cold-chain maintenance is essential.<br><br>Children with a previous episode of intussusception have a significantly higher baseline risk, making vaccination unsafe in this group.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; although storage at 2-8&#176;C is correct, the vaccine is not universally required to be used within 2 hours of opening for all formulations.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; the vaccine should not be given during active acute diarrhoeal illness, as absorption may be impaired.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; both statements are incorrect as per vaccination guidelines.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS592","stem":"A child can make a tower of 3 blocks, runs to mother while sweeping and has a vocabulary of 8-10 words. His developmental age is?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["12 months","15 months","18 months","24 months"],"subject":"Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>A vocabulary of 8-10 meaningful words corresponds to 15 months of age.<br><br>The ability to build a tower of 3 blocks is a fine motor milestone of 15 months.<br><br>Running toward the mother with coordinated movement reflects gross motor development at 15 months.<br><br>The overall combination of language, fine motor, and gross motor milestones best fits 15 months.<br><br>Developmental age is assessed by clustering of milestones, not by a single achievement.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> At this age, vocabulary is limited to 1-3 words, and block tower formation is usually only 2 blocks.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> At this stage, children usually have 15-20 or more words and can build a 4-5 block tower.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Children typically use two-word phrases, have a 50+ word vocabulary, and build 6-7 block towers.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS593","stem":"A child can ride a tricycle, copies a circle, and know their name and gender. The developmental age of this child is?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["2 years","3 years","4 years","5 years"],"subject":"Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Riding a tricycle is a gross motor milestone typically achieved around 3 years of age.<br><br>Ability to copy a circle is a fine motor and visual-motor integration skill seen at 3 years.<br><br>Recognizing and stating name and gender corresponds to language and cognitive development at 3 years.<br><br>The combination of these gross motor, fine motor, and cognitive skills indicates a developmental age of 3 years.<br><br>Assessment is based on clustered milestones rather than a single ability.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> At 2 years, children cannot ride a tricycle, and circle copying is usually not achieved.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> At 4 years, children can copy more complex shapes, and tricycle riding is well mastered.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> At 5 years, children are capable of drawing a triangle or other complex figures, and tricycle use is fully proficient.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS594","stem":"A term baby with birth weight of 2.8 kg is born to a primigravida mother through vaginal delivery and cries immediately after birth. Which of the following statements are correct regarding this initial care after birth?<br>I. The baby should be initiated on breastfeeding within one hour of birth<br>II. The baby should be kept in a separate area from the mother<br>III. The baby should be administered with 0.5 mg of vitamin K1 intramuscularly<br>IV. The baby should be thoroughly examined for congenital malformations from head to toe<br>Select the answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and II","I and III","II and III","I and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Initiation of breastfeeding within one hour promotes bonding, early lactation, and passive immunity through colostrum.<br><br>Thorough head-to-toe examination ensures early detection of congenital malformations or perinatal complications.<br><br>These practices are part of routine newborn care for healthy term infants. (Note: Vitamin K is given 1 mg for term babies, 0.5 mg is for preterm/low birth weight; therefore III is technically incorrect for a 2.8 kg term baby).<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Keeping the baby separate from the mother is not recommended; rooming-in encourages breastfeeding and bonding.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Administering vitamin K1 (0.5-1 mg IM) is recommended, but pairing it with breastfeeding alone does not cover initial newborn examination.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Separation from the mother is not advised, even if vitamin K is given.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS595","stem":"Which one of the following oral drugs may be used in the management of super-refractory status epilepticus?","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["Clonazepam","Clobazam","Lamotrigine","Topiramate"],"subject":"Pediatrics , Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Clobazam is a long-acting benzodiazepine used as an adjunctive oral therapy in patients with super-refractory status epilepticus, especially when intravenous options have been exhausted.<br><br>It helps in maintaining seizure control after initial stabilization with IV benzodiazepines or anesthetic agents.<br><br>Oral administration is useful for transitioning from intensive care to maintenance therapy.<br><br>Clobazam has favorable tolerability and fewer sedative effects compared to other benzodiazepines.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Clonazepam is mainly used for chronic seizure disorders, not routinely for super-refractory status epilepticus.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Lamotrigine is a maintenance antiepileptic but not indicated for acute super-refractory status epilepticus.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Topiramate is an oral antiepileptic for chronic therapy, not first-line in super-refractory status epilepticus.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS596","stem":"Which of the following statements are correct regarding the use of benzodiazepines in the initial management of status epilepticus?<br>I. Upto two doses may be used 5 minutes apart, even if seizures are not controlled.<br>II. For lorazepam, only a single dose should be used, even if seizures are not controlled.<br>III. Dose of midazolam at this stage is 1-1.5 µg/kg/min infusion.<br>IV. Dose of lorazepam and midazolam is 0.1 mg/kg.<br>Select the answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I and III","I and IV","II and III","II and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Pharmacology","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Upto two doses of benzodiazepines (e.g., lorazepam or diazepam) may be administered 5 minutes apart if seizures persist, to achieve seizure control.<br><br>The dose of lorazepam and midazolam for initial management is 0.1 mg/kg IV (lorazepam) or IM/IV (midazolam); this is the standard recommended initial dose.<br><br>Careful dosing is important to avoid respiratory depression while effectively terminating seizures.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; midazolam infusion at 1-1.5 µg/kg/min is used for refractory status epilepticus, not during initial management.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; only a single dose of lorazepam is not mandatory-up to two doses may be given.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; using only a single dose of lorazepam is not consistent with current guidelines.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS597","stem":"Which one of the following statements are correct regarding hypernatremia in children?<br>I. Diabetes insipidus due to a deficiency of antidiuretic hormone (ADH) may cause hypernatremia.<br>II. Addison disease may be associated with hypernatremia.<br>III. Use of boiled skimmed milk can lead to hypernatremia.<br>IV. Use of lactulose can lead to hypernatremia.<br>Select the answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"C","options":["I and II","II and III","I and III","I, II and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Diabetes insipidus due to ADH deficiency leads to free water loss, resulting in hypernatremia.<br><br>Addison disease can cause sodium loss; however, in some cases, impaired renal handling of sodium may contribute to hypernatremia (though it typically causes hyponatremia; the key accepts I and III, rejecting II).<br><br>Use of boiled skimmed milk increases solute load and inadequate free water, predisposing infants to hypernatremia.<br><br>Hypernatremia in children is commonly due to water deficit rather than excessive sodium intake, and lactulose does not directly cause hypernatremia.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; it omits the contribution of boiled skimmed milk to hypernatremia.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; diabetes insipidus is a major cause but is not included here.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; lactulose does not cause hypernatremia.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS598","stem":"Which of the following statements are correct regarding the management of gastrointestinal bleeding in children?<br>I. Somatostatin or octreotide infusion should be used to control upper GI bleeding.<br>II. Endoscopic sclerotherapy (EST) involves endoscopic injection of sclerosant into varices by 2-cmular needle.<br>III. EST has upto 90% efficacy in controlling acute bleeding.<br>IV. Following an episode of acute variceal bleeding, all patients should be started on antibiotic prophylaxis to prevent rebleeding.<br>Select the answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and II","II and III","II and IV","I, II and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics ","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Somatostatin or octreotide infusion is effective in controlling upper GI variceal bleeding in children by reducing portal pressure.<br><br>Endoscopic sclerotherapy (EST) involves injection of a sclerosant into varices to achieve hemostasis.<br><br>Following an episode of acute variceal bleeding, antibiotic prophylaxis is recommended to prevent rebleeding and infections.<br><br>EST efficacy is high, but success rates vary, and additional supportive measures may be required.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Partially correct but omits the need for antibiotic prophylaxis.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; omits the use of somatostatin/octreotide and prophylaxis.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; omits somatostatin/octreotide infusion.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS599","stem":"Which of the following are advantages of endotracheal intubation, in a child requiring pediatric advanced life support?<br>I. Inspiratory time can be controlled<br>II. Positive end-expiratory pressure can be provided<br>III. Peak expiratory pressure can be controlled<br>IV. Reduced risk of aspiration of gastric contents<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"B","options":["I, II and III","I, II and IV","I, III and IV","II, III and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics, Anesthesia","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Inspiratory time can be controlled during mechanical ventilation, optimizing gas exchange.<br><br>Positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP) can be provided to improve alveolar recruitment and oxygenation.<br><br>Reduced risk of aspiration of gastric contents is achieved because the endotracheal tube protects the airway.<br><br>Control of peak expiratory pressure is not a direct advantage; it is more a feature of ventilator settings rather than intubation itself.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; does not include reduced aspiration risk, which is a key advantage.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; omits PEEP, an important benefit for oxygenation.<br><strong>Option D:</strong> Incorrect; omits control of inspiratory time and aspiration protection.<br>"},
{"q":"CMS600","stem":"Which of the following are causes of hypocalcemia in a child?<br>I. Hypomagnesemia<br>II. Hypophosphatemia<br>III. Metabolic acidosis<br>IV. Pseudohypoparathyroidism<br>Select the correct answer using the code given below:","img":"","ans_key":"D","options":["I and II","I and III","III and IV","I and IV"],"subject":"Pediatrics","exam":"UPSC","year_paper":"CMS 2025 Part 1","explanation":"<strong>Solution</strong><br>Hypomagnesemia can lead to hypocalcemia by impairing parathyroid hormone (PTH) secretion and action.<br><br>Pseudohypoparathyroidism is a genetic disorder characterized by resistance to PTH, leading to hypocalcemia despite normal or elevated PTH levels.<br><br>Hypophosphatemia and metabolic acidosis do not directly cause hypocalcemia in children; in fact, acute metabolic acidosis may increase ionized calcium temporarily.<br><br><strong>Other Options:</strong><br><strong>Option A:</strong> Incorrect; hypophosphatemia is not a typical cause of hypocalcemia.<br><strong>Option B:</strong> Incorrect; metabolic acidosis does not directly cause hypocalcemia.<br><strong>Option C:</strong> Incorrect; metabolic acidosis is not a cause of hypocalcemia.<br>"}
];
